description.478:
Data Scientists in Austin are doing incredible data science: making graph models of symptoms and human disease, extracting insight from huge amounts of data in real time, and building tools to make this whole process easier. We founded this Meetup as a forum to showcase that work.

This Meetup is organized by Galvanize. Galvanize offers a data science training programs (a 3 month data science immersive and a year long Masters in Data Sciences accredited through the University of New Haven). Learn more at: http://www.galvanize.com/courses/data-science/www.galvanize.com
description.479:
Comunidad conformada por mujeres apasionadas por la programación y la tecnología.

Misión:

Women Who Code es una organización global sin fines de lucro dedicada a inspirar a las mujeres a sobresalir en carreras de tecnología mediante la creación de una comunidad global e interconectada. El tamaño de la organización se triplicó en 2013, y ha crecido para ser una de las mayores comunidades del mundo de mujeres en ingeniería.

Fortalecimiento:

Women Who Code es una comunidad profesional para mujeres en tecnología. Proporcionamos una vía para que sigan una carrera relacionada con tecnologías, ayudándoles a obtener nuevas habilidades y pulir las ya existentes para su desarrollo profesional, así como proveer un ambiente en donde el networking y las mentorías son valorados.

Iniciativas clave:

Grupos de estudio gratuitosEventos con expertos en la industria de la tecnología e inversionistasHackatonesDesarrollo profesional y liderazgoProgramadoras y aspirantes son bienvenidas. Trae tu laptop e invita a un amigo o amiga!

Apoya a Women Who Code:

Las donaciones a Women Who Code Inc. (#464218859) impactan directamente en nuestra habilidad para operar eficientemente esta organización, nos ayudan a producir nuevos programas que incrementarán nuestro alcance, y nos permiten expandirnos a nuevas ciudades alrededor del mundo asegurando que mujeres y niñas de cualquier lugar tengan la oportunidad de seguir una carrera en tecnología.

Women Who Code (WWCode) is dedicated to providing an empowering experience for everyone who participates in or supports our community, regardless of gender, gender identity and expression, sexual orientation, ability, physical appearance, body size, race, ethnicity, age, religion, or socioeconomic status. Because we value the safety and security of our members and strive to have an inclusive community, we do not tolerate harassment of members or event participants in any form. Our Code of Conduct applies to all events run by Women Who Code, Inc. If you would like to report an incident or contact our leadership team, please submit an incident report form.

Nuestro Código de Conducta aplica para todos los eventos organizados por Women Who Code, Inc.

womenwhocode.com

Twitter | Facebook
description.480:
Somos un grupo de entusiastas y curiosos sobre el lenguaje de programación python, de distintos niveles de conocimientos sobre el lenguaje, los objetivos principales es difundir el lenguaje, fomentar el aprendizaje  y hacer conexiones con mas pythonistas locales.

Para mas información: http://pymty.org
description.481:
San Diego Artificial Intelligence has meetings corresponding to the AI related on-line courses from Udacity, Coursera, edX and others. Join us to get notified about local study groups for these and related classes. Please submit which study groups you're interested in.

"Fifteen people meet each week at the Ansir Innovation Center, a community space with big tables and comfortable chairs, in the Kearny Mesa neighborhood of San Diego." -- New York Times, November 04, 2012.

Anybody with an interest in Artificial Intelligence is welcome to join and attend the events, whether or not you follow any of the courses.
description.482: This group is for anyone that does software development professionally or is aiming to become a professional software developer. The group meets monthly to talk shop over a beer. Occasionally we might have hosted events at local companies or we might have a presentation by one of our members. Mostly though, we get together and rap about our passion...CODE! Come hang out with us.
description.483: A forum to learn about real-world industry applications of Python and related tech. Each month we will invite speakers from local businesses to talk about business critical applications they have implemented in Python and their experience along the way. Contact us directly if you would like to propose speakers or topics for future meetings.
description.484:
Most people believe that black technologists are rare. I chose to believe otherwise.

Why we exist:
This meetup exists because I was damn tired of being the only black person at other tech meetups. I knew I couldn't be the only computer nerd of color in New York, so I started this group to find others like me.

Here's what you need to know:
We aim to be a network of developers in NYC interested in becoming better, learning from each other and networking. We mix hardcore computer science with start-up culture, to create an environment of learning.

Developers of all skill levels are welcome, from experienced hardcore, neckbearded hackers, to n00bs. If you want to be awesome, I hope you can find yourself at home here.

Other awesome meetups:

Blacks in Tech run by the very awesome Mike Street. Mike has grown an awesome network for the business side of tech start-ups and social media. We focus more on programming and technical skills. I attend it.

Hack and Tell: Simply put, a meetup for crazy hacks. This is my second favorite group (after the Black Techies, of course).
description.485:
This group is focused on helping Developer Advocates and Evangelists to share best practices, value-based insights on building communities around API's and cloud based products plus any humorous examples of nerd shepherding.

This group isn't for: Marketing or recruiters to spam with annoying messages.

This group is for: Those who work/live/play in the developer relations space and live in the Bay Area (we cannot accept members who live elsewhere more than 75% of the time).
description.486:
We at RentTesters conduct regular meetups, boot camps and classes for QA professionals. Our goal is to build a solid community of QA testers in the Bay Area, share our experiences and hacks.

Come share your web testing experiences, and learn from other industry leaders.
description.487:
Hey! 

This is a meetup for builders/engineers working on side projects and exploring new technologies. 

I often find that working with others (even if you are not working together directly) is really motivating and a great way to get stuff done. 

The basic idea is this: 

1. We meet somewhere on a Saturday (maybe once a month to start off). 

2. You have something you'd like to work on. (Feel free to join with others if what they are doing sounds even better!) 

3. At the start of the day you share with the group what you plan to work on and whether you are flying solo or open to others collaborating with you. This could be something purely for the enjoyment of learning (e.g. reading a journal, watching conference talks, working on a Kaggle Machine Learning project, playing with yet another JavaScript framework, implementing transducers in LOLCODE etc. etc...), working on an open source library or your own startup project. 

4. At the end of the day you share with the group what you did and what you learned. This can be brief and is mainly for your benefit but hopefully we can learn something from each other or get inspired for our next Side Project.

The goal is to increase our rate of personal learning, ship more side projects and learn a lot from each other. 

Sounds like fun? Let's try it.. :-)
description.488:
Hey Django hackers, let's network, share our knowledge and learn some new things. We're planning meetups in Copenhagen. Once we've picked-up a few members, we'll schedule our first meeting.

While this group is named "The Copenhagen Django Meetup Group", there are lots of interesting topics we can discuss that are not directly Django related, such as Fabric, Celery, Flask, SQLAlchemy etc. etc. Additionally, more operational topics such as using Redis, Memcached, Gunicorn, static file compression, etc. are likely also interesting for Django developers.

Feel free to invite anyone for which you think this group is relevant!
description.489: We are the Berlin chapter of the #flashhacks meetup group. We scrape company data that is published by governments for the opencorporates.com platform. Whether you can write a few lines of code to write a bot, or a journalist who is interested in covering stories on transparency, or a campaigner who champions an open and free world - come along to meet like-minded people and use open data to change the world.
description.490: This group is a place for all Big Data crunchers (Backend Developers, ETL Developers, Data Scientists, Big Data Analysts and DevOps) who want to learn more about Apache Hadoop, a reliable and scalable open source framework for distributed high-performance computing. http://hadoop.apache.org/
description.491: Python developers from Poznan. We have meetings every month.
description.492:
Python Lativa was created with the goal of bringing together developers, learners, employers and technology enthusiasts of all sorts. Everyone is welcome, no matter your skill level or choice of programming language. If you are interested in programming we are interested in you. We believe in a diverse community.

In addition to meeting face-to-face at monthly Meetups, we're on python.lv, Google Plus, Facebook, GitHub and Twitter as @pythonlatvia. Drop in any time to get questions answered!
description.493: We are a group of Systems Engineers and DevOps folks who want to Ansible all the things. Want to learn more about Ansible? Come join us. Already know Ansible well? Come share your knowledge.
description.494:
Um grupo novo que esta tomando forma ainda. Contribua com a gente!
Queremos discutir tópicos relacionamos a Web, Django e novas ideas! Faça parte!

Como estamos nos organizando:

- Local aleatório: Tem um lugar!?? Opa, avisa!

- Encontro mensal.

(Alternando 1 vez durante a semana as 19h e outra aos sábados  10h)
description.495:
Saratov is a great city with growing IT community day by day. The idea of SaratovOpenIt is to give one more chance to discuss interesting themes in friendly atmosphere. SaratovOpenIt is open for any ideas, talks, hackatones, whatever you'd like to bring into community.  You are welcome.

Contacts:

Official site: http://open-it.pro/

Facebook: https://www.facebook.com/groups/SaratovOpenIT/

Vk group: https://vk.com/open_it_saratov

twitter: https://twitter.com/openitpro

youtube: https://www.youtube.com/user/OpenItPro

slideshare: http://www.slideshare.net/Open-IT
description.496:
she codes; is a community of developers aiming to promote women in the field of software development. Our goal is to reach 50% female software developers in the Israeli hi-tech industry within a decade. 

she codes(tau); meets every Tuesday at 5:00pm. You can come to our hacknights to work on your own project, join a project, learn a new programming language, or just come and do your homework. Don't forget to bring your laptop!
description.497:
This is a group for anyone interested in the Python programming language.


We also have a weixin group. Message me to receive an invitation...
description.498:
Jozi Linux User Group (or JoziLUG) is a group for Linux geeks to meetup, listen to an awesome talk about open source technologies and chat. Our goal is to grow a vibrant, supportive Linux user and Open Source community in South Africa.

We meet on the 3rd Monday of every month. Meetings take the form of one or more presentations followed by discussion, dinner and drinks. The talks start at 18:30 and generally end by 20:30, but people are encouraged to stick around afterward and chat with fellow geeks.

If you're keen to get involved, let us know. Suggested topics for presentations are also welcome!
description.499:
Creating an app? Trying to once and for all learn JavaScript? Creating a nonprofit? 

We are a collection of laid-back nerds tinkering on projects in local coffee shops and bars. Swing by if you have a side project that you would like to work on!
description.500: Python Frederick is for people interested in learning and using the Python programming language. We want people to discover the awesome things that Python can do. Whether you're a beginner or a seasoned veteran, join us for some Python inspired fun with like-minded people.
description.501: The purpose of this group is to explore networking technologies, software defined networks (SDN), and Linux programming. We will focus on both the underlay and overlay technologies that are changing the way people build and operate Data Centers. People responsible for Data Centers who want to learn about innovations in Software Defined Networking should join to learn about new innovations as well as from their peers.
description.502: The Codesters teacher meetup is a monthly event for teachers, both new and experienced, to share tips and tricks for teaching kids Python and using the Codesters platform. Codesters is a Python learning environment that makes it easy for students to create games and animations? Our platform extends Python with sprites, events, drawing, animation and even a physics engine. AND, Codesters is free to use. We promise pizza, tshirts, and good conversation about teaching kids Python. Come join us.
description.503:
Come join other enthusiastic computer programmers in the Hudson Valley.

Members of this group should be interested in data structures, algorithms, and writing clever, powerful programs in a variety of languages. There will be a focus during the meetings about writing correct code that fits the philosophy of the language and paradigm it is written in.

Some meetings will be spent going over old programming problems (perhaps from ACM or ICFP or TopCoder) and devising the best solution that we know of. We will write programs, debug them, and learn the best way to solve certain problems.

Some meetings will be actual programming competitions - in groups or individually - so that we can program for fun and improve our skills.

Some meetings will just be small talks on different languages, techniques, or other interesting things going on in the world of programming. Different members are encouraged to talk about what interests them.

And some meetings we may decide to hack on an open source project for fun.

More information can be found at http://hvprogrammers.org.

Join us!
description.504:
Welcome to the Toronto meetup group for elasticsearch!

I have recently moved from Amsterdam to Toronto. In Amsterdam I worked for the Netherlands Institute for Sound and Vision, the national audiovisual archive of the Netherlands and one of the largest archives in Europe. The institute was one of the early adopters of elasticsearch, using it to power the archive's search engine: http://www.elasticsearch.org/case-study/sound-and-vision (if you have a Dutch background or if you are into Dutch cultural heritage, you might enjoy this site: http://in.beeldengeluid.nl).

I have already moved on to another project, but since I could not find an elasticsearch meetup group here in Toronto, I thought that I should start one. I'm happy to share my experience with mappings, settings and bringing an elasticsearch cluster to production, and then let the community take it forward. You all use elasticsearch, don't you?
description.505: The Dayton Dynamic Language User Group is primarily focused on, as you can tell by the name, dynamic languages. If you're interested in Ruby (including Rails), Python (including Django), PHP, Perl, Javascript, Scheme, Lisp, Smalltalk, etc, this is probably the place for you. We try not to talk specifically about things like C and Java, but there are no hard and fast rules (especially if you're comparing them to a dynamic language).
description.506:
This group aims to gather people who are interested in using educational data mining and learning analytics to improve the quality education we are providing.

Brought to you by the organizer from our NY meetup, http://www.meetup.com/Educational-Data-Mining-Learning-An... . We are happy to have it here in Madison as well.

Hosted by 100state
description.507: A user group to discuss and learn using Saltstack for configuration management, service orchestration, and deployment. Meetups are held the fourth Thursday evening of the month.
description.508: Este grupo es para todo aquel que disfrute hacer proyectos DIY ("Do-it-yourself"), sea en software, hardware, mecánica o diseño. Proveemos espacios de colaboración para crear, compartir, y sobre todo para aprender de una manera divertida.
description.509:
We are computer enthusiasts who get together to see, share, learn the latest in Big Data, DevOps, Automation, Continuous Integration, Continuous Deployment, OpenStack, Kubernetes, Docker, Openshift, LXC, Virtualization, and InfoSec. Programming languages like Python, Ruby, GoLang, Scala, Dart, NodeJS, AngularJS, RactJS, BaSh, and more.

There are other IE groups, but a lot of IE techies are working in LA, OC, and other far away places during the week.  Our groups meeting are scheduled with those in mind.
description.510:
Prerequisites

Hackers only. Bring your laptop and a project or tutorial to work on. Recruiters, spectators, etc. are not allowed.


What to expect

Expect to find people sitting around tables talking about and working on their own projects and tutorials. We don't have presentations or structure so bring your own project, tutorial, etc., introduce yourself, ask people "what are you working on", find a seat and get yourself set up, hack away on your project, and have fun.

We frequently see people learning and hacking on software projects using Java, Scala, Ruby, Python, Node, JavaScript, CoffeeScript, among other languages and hardware projects using Arduino.

Our members include beginners working through the Learn Code the Hard Way, Code Academy, One Month Rails, etc. as well as experienced developers working on side projects.

 

Sponsors

 

 

 

 

 

Panda Strike sponsors hack night regularly. Panda Strike is a consultancy focused on rich client, high-performance Web and mobile experiences and lightweight solutions for big data, primarily using CoffeeScript, Node.js, Elaticsearch, and a stack of innovative open source technologies. Panda Strike is hiring talented engineers.


Sponsoring

If you're interested in hosting hack night or sponsoring food or drinks then send me an email.


Contact

You can email me through meetup.com
Follow us on Twitter: @lahacknight
description.511: Google Developer Group Oakdale meets on the first Wednesday of the month at the Stickman Ventures in Oakdale. Our meetings will always be free and open to the general public. However, we may have to limit attendance based on interest and the size of our meeting space. So, early RSVPs on this meetup group are encouraged to ensure your spot at upcoming meetings. Please see the "About" page for more information.
description.512: Work together with other civic enthusiasts to deliver civic innovation in Sacramento! Our weekly hack nights are your chance to roll up your sleeves and help build open-source apps and make Sacramento a better place for everyone. Remember: You don't have to be a coder to hack with us! We welcome designers, thinkers, project managers, social media gurus, data wranglers, problem solvers and all-around civic enthusiasts!
description.513: A monthly, 2-hour unconference in Corvallis about software.
description.514:
The Google Developer Group East Bay (GDGEB) meets semi-regularly in East Bay of San Francisco Bay. We invite our members that developer of Google technology to do brief demos of 5 minutes. This is followed by a technical presentation and/or demonstration of one or more Google technologies from 7:00 to 8:00pm. The time between 8:00pm and 9:00pm is available for longer talks, extended Q&A and/or more informal networking before everyone heads home.

Our general meetings will always be free and open to the general public. We may charge to cover costs for our workshops.

 

GDG East Bay is listed in the official directory of Google Developer groups

 

On Google Plus

https://plus.google.com/u/0/107682656760746559369/about
description.515:
This is a meet up group for women based in or around Edinburgh, involved or interested in python programming. All levels are welcome, from professional programmers to those completely new to programming of any sort! We plan to have informal monthly meetups, as well as occasional talks and other one-off events. 

PyLadies is an international mentorship group with a focus on helping more women become active participants and leaders in the Python open-source community. Our mission is to promote, educate and advance a diverse Python community through outreach, education, conferences, events and social gatherings. PyLadies also aims to provide a friendly support network for women and a bridge to the larger Python world. Anyone with an interest in Python is encouraged to participate! Follow us on Twitter @PyLadiesEdin.
description.516: Python Perú es la Comunidad de estudiantes, profesionales e interesados en tener un espacio donde conversar, preguntar e intercambiar ideas todo acerca del lenguaje de programación Python
description.517:
Max/MSP is a software environment that makes it easy to prototype interactive systems in minutes.

It's used worldwide to run digital art installations, prototype new musical instruments, craft maxForLive devices or drive any machine where realtime control is critical.

This group is intended for anyone interested in learning the basics, in sharing specific skills with other members or looking for help on a project where you think Max could help. You don't need to be a programmer to get started.

Depending on members' interests, we'll do hands-on sessions to build music (or noise) machines, samplers, sequencers, controllers, look into classic errors or good practices, organise live coding jam sessions, just experiment with generative art ideas. More on Max: http://www.cycling74.com
description.518:
This is a group for anyone interested in Python/Django and Open Source development. All skills levels are welcome. We have been organizing meetup events for  3 years on a monthly basis in the Suisse romande area (mostly in Lausanne).

We are looking forward to meeting you and to hearing from you: we're always looking for speakers to tell their story. Join us!
description.519: Ruby And Rails community in Latvia and city as Riga, Ventspils, Liepaja, Valmiera, Jelgava and etc.
description.520:
We organize regular monthly meetups for people interested in all things Python. The meetup are organized by SPy civic association. More can be found on association's website. All meetup attendees must honor our Code of Conduct.


If you are interested in Python and are somewhere near Bratislava, you should join us. You can be complete novice or experienced programmer, everybody is welcome.
description.521: In SPACE (EventSpace.By) we host best technology meetups, communities gatherings, workshops and conferences. Join IT Community of Belarus!
description.522: Rejoignez-nous pour tout apprendre sur le logiciel Odoo (ancien OpenERP). Si vous souhaitez simplement connaitre les aspects fonctionnels (basiques et avancés), ou pouvoir développer des modules adaptés pour votre entreprise ou pour vos clients, ce groupe est fait pour vous. Que vous soyez chef d'entreprise, informaticien, développeur ou simple utilisateur, tous les niveaux sont les bienvenus... Faisons bouger le Cameroun !
description.523: This is a group for new and experienced developers interested or already using the Python programming language. If you are an experienced Python programmer who lives or is visiting Addis, you are more than welcome to attend this meetup or do a presentation on any subject related to Python including best practices, library usages, do's and don't do's from your experience. If you are new to Python programming language, you are also welcome to attend this meetup, meet other people with similar interests and participate in sharing and newbie nurturing environment we hope this group will be.
description.524: The "Karachi Raspberry Pi Jam" is a hands-on style event that will organize meetups monthly. From the outset it  will be helping people the chance to turn up and work on Pi projects together. All sorts of people are made welcome, from teachers, parents and children to professional software developers and hardware hackers.
description.525:
Mission:

Women Who Code is a global nonprofit organization dedicated to inspiring women to excel in technology careers by creating a global, connected community of women in technology. The organization tripled in 2013 and has grown to be one of the largest communities of women engineers in the world.

Empowerment:

Women Who code is a professional community for women in tech. We provide an avenue for women to pursue a career in technology, help them gain new skills and hone existing skills for professional advancement, and foster environments where networking and mentorship are valued.

Key Initiatives:

Free technical study groups

Events featuring influential tech industry experts and investors

Hack events

Career and leadership development

Current and aspiring coders are welcome. 

Bring your laptop and a friend! 

Support Women Who Code:

Donating to Women Who Code, Inc. (#46-4218859) directly impacts our ability to efficiently run this growing organization, helps us produce new programs that will increase our reach, and enables us to expand into new cities around the world ensuring that women and girls everywhere have the opportunity to pursue a career in technology.

Women Who Code (WWCode) is dedicated to providing an empowering experience for everyone who participates in or supports our community, regardless of gender, gender identity and expression, sexual orientation, ability, physical appearance, body size, race, ethnicity, age, religion, or socioeconomic status. Because we value the safety and security of our members and strive to have an inclusive community, we do not tolerate harassment of members or event participants in any form. Our Code of Conduct applies to all events run by Women Who Code, Inc. If you would like to report an incident or contact our leadership team, please submit an incident report form.

WomenWhoCode.com

Twitter | Facebook
description.526: Great things can happen when small groups of focused teams get together to learn. Thats what the Code Lounge is all about - we seek to get people to lend their lounges for at least six hours on a weekend (or other public holiday) to allow like minded developers to congregate and learn. Individual cells can be running concurrently, they can even cover the same topics and we encourage tools like Google Hangouts or Skype to allow others to participate. Its cosy. Its fun. Its an environment where people want to learn, want to change and want to get better. If that sounds like you, welcome to the Code Lounge.
description.527:
Functional Christchurch is for software people that want to hone their development skills. Consider this meet-up if: 

• you are interested in functional programming 

• want to share your skills, experience or examples of what you've achieved

• you want to help cultivate a community of functional software practice in Christchurch
description.528:
A group which will meet both physically and virtually on a regular basis to work together on advancing the core codebase and adoption of CKAN.

See ckan.org to learn more about this open source project built on Python and used around the world to support Open Data initiatives. Take a look at http://instances.ckan.org to see where CKAN is being used near you.

The primary purpose of this meetup is to rally contributors and support their efforts in advancing the CKAN roadmap (http://ckan.org/developers/roadmap/). We'll tie in with the Technical Team to support consistent and thoughtful development of CKAN over regular release cycles (http://ckan.org/about/technical-team/).

The secondary purpose of this meetup will be to support awareness and user adoption via both technical and non technical presentations from members. We'll aim to publish regularly to ckan.org with great examples of CKAN platforms, extensions and integrations.
description.529:
This group is a place where developers of all kinds can come together and hack on anything that they'd like or work with someone else.  We'll get together on the 3rd Tuesday of each month.  We'll start about 6:30pm and go until 9:00ish.  We're always on the lookout for sponsors to help with food and drink!

The agenda is very straight forward. First we'll introduce ourselves.  Then it's time to start hacking!

Any software project, any programming language, any platform, any reason - everyone who's looking to write some code (or pair program) is welcome. Take some time to work on that side project, learn a new skill, and make some new friends by coming out to Buxmont OpenHack.
description.530:
Greetings hacker or hacker-to-be! Welcome to the CLT Hacker Society - a group of like minded individuals who share interests in white, gray and black hat hacking, programming, web sec, networking, infosec, anonymity, opsec, the open source movement, decentralization, bitcoin, free market trade, entrepreneurship and more.

Our main objectives consist of sharing knowledge and helping others. Our goal is to have consistent social gatherings, workshops, labs, guest speakers, events and more.
description.531: Flint Area Coders: Our coding Meetup is an ongoing platform for Flint area individuals to explore, learn, and present their coding progress. We will gather together every month for mini lessons & update one another on coding development. We hope that the meetup will encourage and nurture unforeseen collaborations between like-minded individuals & we encourage you to join! Come meet others in the community are interested in learning how to code & hanging out with us!
description.533: The Chicago Data Science & Engineering Group focuses on learning and implementing techniques in data science, engineering, statistics, machine learning, and visualization. This is is a language agnostic group and all technologies and tools are welcome including Python, Scala, Hadoop, Spark, Clojure, R, etc. This is an open space for learning and sharing. Beginners welcome.
description.534: We are a bunch of people who want to get together to learn, teach, share and discuss all things related to the Python programming language and other programming topics. We love Python but we also love coding languages in general. For more details, check out http://py-cu.org.
description.535: The OrlandoPy(thon) User Group is for users, enthusiasts, and students in Orlando, Florida, interested in the Python computer programming language. We meet monthly to discuss and present emerging issues and interesting projects in Python, practice our skill, and trade stories from the workforce. All skill levels are welcome.
description.536: A group for learning, sharing, collaborating, networking - and having fun sponsored by New Relic. This is for anyone developing critical applications / or responsible for running applications - a true DevOps oriented group. We focus on sharing, learning, events, and also fun-oriented events. If you are a Developer, Product Manager, Digital Innovation specialist, or you run Apps in Production this is the group for you! www.newrelic.com/apm
description.537:
High quality, free coding workshops and hackathons by AT&T.

We only hold a couple of coding workshops or hackathons in the Dallas area each year, so you won't get a lot of messages from us. But when we do return you'll be the first to know! So join to stay up-to-date on our future developer events.
description.538: This group is for anyone in the Austin area interested Natural Language Processing. Topics may include computational linguistics, machine learning, text analytics, data mining, information extraction, speech processing, sentiment analysis, etc. Note: this group has nothing to do with Neuro Linguistic Programming.
description.539:
Welcome to Spokane Python User Group, the local Python Meetup Group! We have a wide range of topics all related to Python, Web Development, and Open Source technology. We meet on the 3rd Tuesday each month. 

All meetings are free, and we encourage everyone to participate and get involved and help grow the Python community. After each meeting we typically go to a nearby restaurant/bar/pub for more informal discussion. We base all our meetings from attendee suggestions. If you have an idea for a topic that you would like to see (or present), please let the organizers know!
description.540:
This community group is intended to discuss the Python Programming Language in the Orange County, California area.

    Topics of discussion...

      are set by the group members.

      suggested topics include:

        use of the Python Programming Language

        specific Applications Written in Python

        Python-based Web Frameworks (a comparsion of 6)

        Python CMS(Content Management System)s

        Python Systems Administration

        Python systems engineering (group example)

        alternative implementations of Python including Jython, IronPython, PyPy, and Cython

        Python Performance Tips & issues

        Python libraries especially the Python Standard Library

        Useful Python Modules members have found

        and more.

Please Join us!
description.541: Meetings posted at OCLUG.org and hosted at CSUF.
description.542:
Computer programming sessions for young programmers in grades 3–12, in or near Lamorinda (Lafayette, Moraga, Orinda), run by experienced software developer and teacher Dave Briccetti. Sessions usually consist of instruction, coding time, and a lot of collaboration and learning from each other. Kids will bring a laptop, and learn to program computers using environments or languages like Tynker, Scratch, Python, Scala and JavaScript. Some sessions will be free, but most will have a fee for the instructor’s time (and sometimes room rental). For kids-only sessions (most of them), parents may observe if space permits.

For a sample of possible topics, and to see the instructor in action, see his YouTube channel.

Some sessions will take place over Google+ Hangouts. Join the Young Programmers community if you are interested in these.
description.543: Flask is a microframework for Python based on Werkzeug, Jinja 2 and good intentions.
description.544: San Francisco PyData is a group for data nerds who use Python and the available libraries: Matplotlib, NumPy, Pandas, NetworkX, etc.
description.545:
Are you a developer interested in learning how to summarize, visualize and interpret your data?

description.548:
Chapitre français de l'association internationale PyLadies. Nous sommes un groupe international de mentoring qui a pour objectif d'aider les femmes (cis et trans), les hommes trans, les genderqueer ou les agenré⋅e⋅s à devenir des membres actifs et des leaders dans la communauté open-source Python.

N'hésitez pas à venir, quelque soit votre niveau en Python :)

---

French chapter of Pyladies. We are an international mentorship group with a focus on helping more women, trans men, genderqueer or agender, become active participants and leaders in the Python open-source community.

Our mission is to promote and advance a diverse Python community through outreach, education, conferences, events and social gatherings.

We will organized two diferents types of events: Non-mixed code workshops and talks where cis men can come only if they are invited by someone else (+1).

Don't be afraid to come: we're beginer friendly :)

description.557:
Mission:

Women Who Code is a global nonprofit organization dedicated to inspiring women to excel in technology careers by creating a global, connected community of women in technology. The organization tripled in 2013 and has grown to be one of the largest communities of women engineers in the world.

Empowerment:

Women Who code is a professional community for women in tech. We provide an avenue for women to pursue a career in technology, help them gain new skills and hone existing skills for professional advancement, and foster environments where networking and mentorship are valued.

Key Initiatives:

Free technical study groups

Events featuring influential tech industry experts and investors

Hack events

Career and leadership development

Current and aspiring coders are welcome. 

Bring your laptop and a friend! 

Support Women Who Code:

Donating to Women Who Code, Inc. (#46-4218859) directly impacts our ability to efficiently run this growing organization, helps us produce new programs that will increase our reach, and enables us to expand into new cities around the world ensuring that women and girls everywhere have the opportunity to pursue a career in technology.

Women Who Code (WWCode) is dedicated to providing an empowering experience for everyone who participates in or supports our community, regardless of gender, gender identity and expression, sexual orientation, ability, physical appearance, body size, race, ethnicity, age, religion, or socioeconomic status. Because we value the safety and security of our members and strive to have an inclusive community, we do not tolerate harassment of members or event participants in any form. Our Code of Conduct applies to all events run by Women Who Code, Inc. If you would like to report an incident or contact our leadership team, please submit an incident report form.

WomenWhoCode.com

description.603:
We are the Salt Lake City chapter of an international mentorship group with a focus on helping more women become active participants and leaders in the Python open-source community. Our mission is to promote, educate and advance a diverse Python community through outreach, education, conferences, events and social gatherings. PyLadies also aims to provide a friendly support network for women and a bridge to the larger Python world. Anyone with an interest in Python is encouraged to participate!

"I spent a lot of time thinking I wasn't qualified for this." --female Stanford computer science student

Several of us are using Udacity CS 101 as our introduction to programming, and there are lots more good introductory materials we can point you to. What matters most is to have a community of people who will support you as you learn new concepts. If you have an interest, you can do it. It just takes time and practice.

P r a c t i c e.          I t ' s    w h a t    w e    d o.

"There's some very good statistics . . . that show that when women don't succeed at first, they blame themselves, and men [who don't succeed at first] blame the course or the test."  --Eric Roberts, professor of Computer Science at Stanford

"They need to know that just because they didn't construct a floppy disk at age five doesn't mean they shouldn't be there." --Erin Wakefield, Intel

"Generally, guys in engineering are motivated by coolness. Women are motivated by their impact to help." Wakefield hit a point in her career when she felt apathetic about her work; she was building a graphic chip and hated that she was working her butt off to allow some kid to play Halo with better explosions. As the chip developed, though, the Mayo clinic got involved, adding a medical imaging component to the project. She had found a source of motivation. http://management.fortune.cnn.com/2012/02/2...
description.604: Python es lo mejor y por eso nos reunimos para dialogar acerca de este lenguaje de programacion.
description.605:
ABOUT US

HackerNest is a grassroots nonprofit organization that runs unpretentious community events and epic, meaningful, universally-acclaimed hackathons. Our mission is economic development through technological proliferation. Check us out >>> Facebook  |  Twitter  |  Wikipedia

Connecting people is awesome. And community good breeds fab karma. We cram smart, accomplished techies into a room, often with free drinks. Our relaxed, down-to-earth Tech Socials are now Canada’s largest tech meetups and growing quite quickly internationally. Our membership is diverse and highly technical. Developers, designers, engineers, social media/business folk, entrepreneurs, investors, etc. regularly gather to socialize, talk tech, hear the occasional speaker or watch a demo, and meet future co-founders, employees, funders, and friends.

Our formula: laid back atmosphere + free drinks + brilliant people = fireworks. We're not scienticians, but this seems to work. We became Canada's largest tech meetups in a year, before even leaving Toronto. Today we have "splinter cells" in multiple cities internationally. Our goal is to complement and strengthen existing nerd ecosystems – we come in peace. We hail the ideal of a strong and supportive tech community - pretty much anyone that isn't a jerk can be a part of it, so we have a strict no-douchebag policy.

Interested in running HackerNest in your city? Take a look at the FAQ. Whoa, longest description evaaar. Need to know more? Here's some answers. 

RSVP to get a custom, hand-written nametag. This is important, because people without nametags aren't even really people. There, we said it. :)

Facebook  |  Twitter  |  Wikipedia

SOME DETAILS:

********

When: Pretty darned regularly. Check back!

Format: Relaxed. Hang, talk tech, occasionally a speaker, plot to take over the world, etc.

Where: Usually in the large private office of a tech company (have a venue?)

At any given HackerNest meetup, you may find people who are:

developing incredibly snazzy Ruby (most likely on Rails) applications - heady hardcore designer types - PHP/Perl/.NET/Python/django addicts - ...Fortran devs?! - looking for a tech/entrepreneur/new business story to cover - Objective-C experts and iPhone/iPad/Apple product pundits - engineers and managers and CTOs looking for co-founders to join their angel/VC-backed tech startup - looking to write articles/stories about the obscure, interesting, hilarious hacks you've pulled off - totally oblivious and just wandered in because they heard there was booze (!?) - building a top-secret app out of their basement that's going to change the way the world does X; like "Facebook for Squirrels" - scrambling to find a partner to work with on a well-paying contract that's just a wee bit too much workload for the anticipated deadline - heroes, because they're part of the burgeoning community that will reverse all this insane brain-drain - incredibly talented, smart, entrepreneurial go-getters who are absolutely dangerous to the status quo - pretty bloody interesting, because seriously, if they're coming out for drinks ON A MONDAY (or Tuesday, or Wednesday) NIGHT... they've gotta be.

Chances are, you'll fit right in if you're a(n):

software or hardware hacker/h4ck3r (or maybe just a hack) - coder/developer/programmer/designer, UX-oriented, or just like making things pretty - biotech/electrical/computer or basically any kind of engineer - network/network/system/IT administrator - front/back-end specialist - angel investor - demon investor - venture capitalist - venture communist - tech enthusiast - tech/entrepreneur-oriented media/journalist - OCD blogger/Tweeter - bloodthirsty recruiter looking to poach developers - internet mogul - nerd/geek/freak/tweak - entrepreneur - SEO/SEM pro - writer/project manager/business analyst - 1337 individual - etc., etc.


...and aren't a douchebag. <3

description.627:
ABOUT US

Now Canada's largest tech meetups, and growing internationally, eh.

RSVP to get a nametag. This is important, because people without nametags aren't even really people. There, we said it. :) Check us out >>> Facebook | Twitter

HackerNest is an international nonprofit community movement focused on building supportive Silicon Valley like tech communities in every city - strengthening local tech ecosystems globally through unpretentious social events and hackathons. We’re nurturing cohesive communities today to empower them with more relevant and accessible peer-based tech education tomorrow.

Connecting people is awesome. And community good breeds fab karma.

We cram smart, accomplished people into a room with free beer. Our relaxed, down-to-earth Tech Socials are now Canada’s largest tech meetups.

Our membership - diverse and highly technical. Developers, designers, engineers, social media/business folk, entrepreneurs, investors, etc. regularly gather to socialize, talk tech, maybe hear speakers or watch demos, and meet future co-founders, employees, funders, and friends. Strict no-douchebag policy.

Global. We want an international network of HackerNest “splinter cells” to pop up everywhere – from underserved cities to high-growth innovation centers – to rescue nerds from isolated basements, offices, and code tunnel vision.

We love hardcore nerdcore. Tech folks, tech events, tech love. Our formula: laid back atmosphere + free drinks + brilliant people = fireworks

We're not scienticians, but the formula seems to work: we became Canada's largest tech meetups in a year, before even leaving Toronto. Today we have "splinter cells" in multiple cities internationally.

Our goal is to complement and strengthen existing nerd ecosystems – we come in peace. This isn't a business; nobody owns HackerNest. Conceptually, it is the ideal of a strong and supportive tech community - pretty much anyone that isn't a jerk can be a part of it.

Interested in running HackerNest in your city? Take a look at the FAQ.

---->---

Whoa, longest descriptions evaaar. Need more? Here's some answers. Don't forget to check us out >>> Facebook | Twitter

---->---

Here's more pictures of our Tech Socials and hackathons:

********

When: Pretty darned regularly. Check back!

Format: Relaxed. Hang, talk tech, occasionally a speaker, plot to take over the world, etc.

Where: Usually in the large private office of a tech company (have a venue?)

At any given HackerNest meetup, you may find people who are:

developing incredibly snazzy Ruby (most likely on Rails) applications - heady hardcore designer typesPHP/Perl/.NET/Python/django addicts - ...Fortran devs?! - looking for a tech/entrepreneur/new business story to cover - Objective-C experts and iPhone/iPad/Apple product pundits - engineers and managers and CTOs looking for co-founders to join their angel/VC-backed tech startup - looking to write articles/stories about the obscure/interesting/hilarious hacks you've pulled off - totally oblivious and just wandered in because they heard there was booze (!?) - building a top-secret app out of their basement that's going to change the way the world does X; like "Facebook for Squirrels" - scrambling to find a partner to work with on a well-paying contract that's just a wee bit too much workload for the anticipated deadline - heroes, because they're part of the burgeoning community that will reverse all this insane brain-drain - incredibly talented, smart, entrepreneurial go-getters who are absolutely dangerous to the status quo - pretty bloody interesting, because seriously, if they're coming out for drinks ON A MONDAY (or Tuesday, or Wednesday) NIGHT... they've gotta be

Chances are, you'll fit right in if you're a(n):

• software or hardware hacker/h4ck3r (or maybe just a hack)

• coder/developer/programmer/brogrammerdesigner, UX-oriented, or just like making things pretty

• biotech/electrical/computer or basically any kind of engineer 

• network/network/system/IT administrator

• front/back-end specialist

• angel investor

• demon investor

• venture capitalist

• venture communist

• tech enthusiast

• tech/entrepreneur-oriented media/journalist

• OCD blogger/Tweeter

• bloodthirsty recruiter looking to poach developers

• internet mogul

• nerd/geek/freak/tweak

• entrepreneur

• SEO/SEM pro

• writer/project manager/business analyst

• 1337 individual

• etc., etc.

...and aren't a douchebag. <3

It is highly recommended members review the topic presented before the Meetup and have a general idea of the technologies that are being discussed. 

All Meetups are free! At each meeting, there will be two 15 minute presentations and each will consist of a brief history of the technology and a technical problem to solve. At the end of each presentation, the audience will take turns deciding on what is the best strategy to use. A panel of experts will also give their take on what they feel is the best solution to the problem.

We will pair up and practice on a kata in order to learn and apply the values, principles, and disciplines of software craftsmanship. Come with your laptop equipped with your favorite programming and automated unit testing environment. Be prepared to pair up, learn, share and have fun!

 

We thank Washington,DC Software Craftsmanship group for their help with starting up this group in Baltimore.

From engineering to operations to data science, this group will explore stories of the successes and battle scars of scaling the infrastructure to millions of users.

Everyone is welcome and encouraged to come and learn what makes iHeartRadio tick.
description.668:
Programming 101: Pen and Paper Coding is an introductory programming class taught using pen and paper only in NYC. 

Our method helps prevent any distractions that occur when using a computer too early on in the learning process, while students focus on getting a solid grasp of the fundamentals of computer programming. 

The goals of the course are ambitious, and the curriculum covers a lot of the materials taught in a typical “Programming 101” course at computer science departments around the world.  

The course consists of 5 sessions, meeting once a week for five consecutive weeks. Group size is between 4-8 students + an experienced instructor. The course fee is $399, and includes all 5 sessions, video recordings of each class, as well as a textbook written by the main instructor specifically for this course. The course is held at Impact Hub (394 Broadway @ Walker St) (nyc.impacthub.net).

Join this Meetup group to stay informed about our courses and visit www.penpapercoding.com for more information!

Come, join us for a dynamic programming class that delivers!

The Pen and Paper Coding Team
description.669:
This is a group for anyone interested in Flask, Python, web development, and any related technologies.

 

To stay up to date with group events, follow us on Twitter @FlaskNYC.

 

Want to read up on Flask?
description.670:
We are exploring answers for questions such as: How do you know that the data you are looking at is the data you think you are looking at? How fast can a domain expert, but very likely a technical layperson, get understandable answers to his/her questions if there are so many ways and places where your data is stored? How you make sure that your reports will not be disrupted when you change any of the internal systems to a different kind?


Data Brewery is a knowledge sharing and sometimes lightly hacking community around data warehousing and its application. Anyone is welcome, whether you have small data or big data, whether your data is open or not, whether you are non-profit organisation or a corporation.


The topics are mostly about master data management, data quality, conceptual data modelling, metadata and ETL. We bring together data users (not necessarily with technical background) and data engineers to share their stories, ask questions and come up with solutions. 


From time-to-time we will also be talking about or lightly hacking on data warehousing libraries and applications. We are putting together a collection of open-source tools that anyone would be able to use to help them with their data problems. Language of our choice is Python.
description.671: NYC Tech Recruiters is creating a community of Tech Recruiters coming together to meet like-minded Recruiters and exchange ideas and best practices in the evolving Tech scene in NYC. Within this community we are promoting mentoring along with professional development within a general forum for Tech Recruiters to share their experiences. And we plan to have fun doing it. Software engineers are also welcomed to join this group to gain knowledge and give feedback on what they seek from a technical recruiting experience. Please join this group if you're a technical recruiter looking to meet with other Recruiters in New York City and expand your experience and education level on a variety of recruiting issues that face the recruiting industry in the realm of Social Media.
description.672:
Are you coding a Django app? So are we! We want to get together and hack with other New Yorkers, share tips, host office hours, and basically try to make it as easy and socially rewarding as possible for us Django folks.

This group is for hackers. Our meetups will be about writing code, so if you're not doing that, there are probably better meetups for you to join. This definitely isn't meant to be anyone's free recruiting pool. We do welcome students, people just getting started, developer evangelists and other folks who can help us code better.
description.673:
If you've ever visited Hacker News, you've almost certainly seen the "Show HN" or "Ask HN" posts. Well, it's time to get off the Internet and tell us about it face to face. We'll provide you with our honest feedback, you provide us with a great hack or idea.

We'll give you 5 minutes to show off your tool, hack, library (did you just write a library to access the Meetup API in Go!?), whatever. We're language / software/ hardware agnostic, so it's all fair game.

After you present, it's an open forum. The audience will ask questions and provide feedback. We want to enable as much participation as possible at these meetups, so you'd better be able to take criticism and dish it out (all within reason of course).

Our mailing list has a strict no recruiters and no promotion of commercial projects policy. If you think that your message to the list might not be appropriate, either run it by the organizers, or don't send it! Violators will be banned as soon as possible--no questions asked!
description.674: This is a group for anyone interested in research concerning artificial neural networks, deep learning, and so on. The format varies between discussion groups, guest speakers, and tutorials. Proposed topics include: training deep belief networks with unsupervised pre-training/supervised finetuning, recurrent neural networks, different optimization methods, scalable architectures for large networks across clusters, practical GPU programming (with Python!), NNs for NLP, using NNs in robotics, visualizations to monitor NN learning, and other stuff specific to these areas of research. Recent developments in this area of research show a lot of promise, but very few people within the machine learning community have any practical experience with these methods. Since there's so few of us, we should get together and share notes!
description.675: This is a group for anyone passionate about learning programming, computer science, and how the internet works. Each meetup has a specific project that you will have completed by the end of the session. All we ask is that you come with an open mind and excitement. At this time you must provide your own computer but please feel free to message one of our organizers if you do not have access to a computer and we will see what we can do. Pizza Values: - Empathy - Inclusivity - Optimism - Simplicity
description.676: This is a group for people interested in using Python to work with Excel spreadsheets. Anyone who wants to do more with Excel - whether you're a beginner, Excel power user, or VBA expert - is welcome to join!
description.677:
We're a group dedicated to helping new software developers get started. We welcome mentors, educators, software developers of all skill levels, and companies interested in hiring new developers for internships, apprenticeships, first-hires, or junior roles.

As mentors, instructors and educators, how do we develop curricula that gets developers ready for software development? How do we test and iterate?

As software developers and architects, how do we write codebases that are straightforward and clean? How do we best optimize for productivity from newer developers?

As newer software developers, how do we filter out the noise? How do we find career coaching and mentorship? How do we move from a structured learning environment to a self-taught one?

There are a lot of people in the software community in NYC who want to help new developers succeed. That's our goal.

We'll be hosting roundtable discussions, planning sessions, and other, more tech-focused events.
description.678: Millions of users listen to Spotify's streaming music service world wide. Behind the scenes is a world class technology organization that innovates hard to make the music easy. description.679:
In 1826 Josiah Holbrook organized the Millbury Branch Number 1 of the American Lyceum with the goal of bringing lifelong education through presentation and spirited debate to everyone. Mr. Holbrook’s great hope was to bring about a general and universal diffusion of knowledge regardless of age, gender or station. Taking the name “Lyceum” from Aristotle’s school, Mr. Holbrook’s efforts resulted in the organization of thousands of local Lyceums and the brief formation of a National Lyceum.

At Axial, we agree strongly with Mr. Holbrook that education is a lifelong exercise. We believe that curiosity and ingenuity are critically important and that you should engage in debate with friends, colleagues and experts on a variety of topics frequently and vigorously.

In the spirit of the 19th century Lyceum movement, we invite domain experts to our offices every month to give a presentation or participate in a panel discussion. Our doors are open to anyone interested in joining the debate (and of course, there’s always the free Sixpoint). 

The Axial Corps of Engineers is a team of technologists dedicated to pragmatically and predictably shipping innovative software. Some people would say we’re flip-floppers, but we reserve the right to change our minds when new evidence is presented. The best argument, implementation or design on any given day is the one we’ll favor at Axial, not the one coming from the person with the highest rank, title or most pull. We value practical consideration and self-restraint backed by solid communication over rockstars, samurais and ninjas.

We’ll use a framework, tool, language or approach as soon as it becomes obvious that it’s well supported, stable, low maintenance and the right tool for the job.

*We kindly ask that agency recruiters refrain from attending.

**If you feel like you have a relevant talk that you'd like to present, send some information over to alex.steinberg@axial.net.

• Summits & Mini Camps  Day (Fri Jul 17)

• Sessions  & Keynote Day (Sat Jul 18)

Our attendees  are primarily open source software developers, but also include a mix of technical strategists, decision makers, designers, trainers and project managers.

Our sessions  are focused on open source languages (PHP, Python, JS, etc.) and related open source frameworks/libraries (Angular, Ember, Backbone, Meteor, Django, Drupal, Symfony, D3, etc.). We also include sessions on the web platform use to help host these sites and apps created with thes open source tools (e.g., Acquia, AWS, Bluemix/IBM, Digital Ocean, Galaxy, Google Cloud, OpenShift, Pantheon, etc.).

Meaning the "what" is more important than the "how" in regards to joining the group. That is to say the group is generally open to those who develop code they release to the public. The group is also open to those who are new to programming and looking opportunities to learn.

Our Meetings are normally either social (find help, get help) or hands on (workshop or group project) maybe a mix of both.

The regular "Find help, get help" meeting format is a bit different but simple. Members suggest issues they are dealing with or impending interest on the meet-up event page. Depending on what is appropriate, the meeting may break out into separate groups for individual topics or just have a full group discussion. The main goal is having the opportunity to get new perspective, with the recognition that solutions or complete understanding may still be hard to come by. description.753:

description.754:
Mission:

Women Who Code is a global nonprofit organization dedicated to inspiring women to excel in technology careers by creating a global, connected community of women in technology. The organization tripled in 2013 and has grown to be one of the largest communities of women engineers in the world.

Empowerment:

Women Who code is a professional community for women in tech. We provide an avenue for women to pursue a career in technology, help them gain new skills and hone existing skills for professional advancement, and foster environments where networking and mentorship are valued.

Key Initiatives:

Free technical study groups

Events featuring influential tech industry experts and investors

Hack events

Career and leadership development

Current and aspiring coders are welcome. 

Bring your laptop and a friend! 

Support Women Who Code:

Donating to Women Who Code, Inc. (#46-4218859) directly impacts our ability to efficiently run this growing organization, helps us produce new programs that will increase our reach, and enables us to expand into new cities around the world ensuring that women and girls everywhere have the opportunity to pursue a career in technology.

Women Who Code (WWCode) is dedicated to providing an empowering experience for everyone who participates in or supports our community, regardless of gender, gender identity and expression, sexual orientation, ability, physical appearance, body size, race, ethnicity, age, religion, or socioeconomic status. Because we value the safety and security of our members and strive to have an inclusive community, we do not tolerate harassment of members or event participants in any form. Our Code of Conduct applies to all events run by Women Who Code, Inc. If you would like to report an incident or contact our leadership team, please submit an incident report form.

WomenWhoCode.com

Twitter | Facebook

This group is for Chicago Area Freelancers (be it developers, designers, copywriters, photographers, lawyers, plumbers, whatever). We are all makes and models who get together and have a drink, discuss our work, share tips and techniques, and find full time and contract work opportunities.

We invite group members to submit ideas to talk about.  Bring a laptop or a tablet, a sketchpad or an etch-a-sketch.  We don't care.

We have just a few simple rules:

1) (Starting in 2014) We charge a bar minimum for meetups so that we ensure quality attendance (Really, it's just somewhere between $1-3).

2) It's social, so we expect people to talk. We shouldn't have to remind folks, but if there's a speaker, please have common decency and do not disturb others.

Here's some more resources for our group that keep coming up:

1) Breaking the time barrier. It's a great read and helps people realize how to get beyond just thinking about our skill set as an hourly committment, but thinking about value add: https://breakingthetimebarrier.freshbooks.com/

2) Freelancer's Bible is a great resource for anyone striking out on their own: http://www.amazon.com/The-Freelancers-Bible-Everything-Career/dp/076116488X

3) Freelancer's Guild (I couldn't find a URL but googling for it brings a bunch of results up).

4) The SBA. It's here to help us. Let's help them help us: http://www.sba.gov/offices/district/il/chicago

That's it!

Welcome and enjoy!

description.780:
You get 5 minutes to show off what you've built (tool, hack, library, etc). We're language and technology agnostic, so it's all fair game.  Then the audience gets 5 minutes to ask you questions about it.

While all technology is fair game, there are a few rules:

  • No deckware/varporware. It doesn't have to be completely finished or polished, but it does need to be something you've actually made.
  • No startup pitches. Ever.
  • No work projects [1]. No presentations that are just promoting commercial software.

We're inspired by the original Hack and Tell in NYC, like many others.

[1]: Let me clarify the "no job projects" rule. We want to promote the projects that people do in their spare time, for fun, or utility, and not the kinds of projects that are only applicable to people who work in your company, or your direct clients. On the other hand, there may be a project that you've built primarily at work, that solves a *general* problem that your company has allowed you to release with a libre license--this is usually fine.
description.781:
The Zen of Python, by Tim Peters
Beautiful is better than ugly.
Explicit is better than implicit.
Simple is better than complex.
Complex is better than complicated.
Flat is better than nested.
Sparse is better than dense.
Readability counts.
Special cases aren't special enough to break the rules.
Although practicality beats purity.
Errors should never pass silently.
Unless explicitly silenced.
In the face of ambiguity, refuse the temptation to guess.
There should be one-- and preferably only one --obvious way to do it.
Although that way may not be obvious at first unless you're Dutch.
Now is better than never.
Although never is often better than *right* now.
If the implementation is hard to explain, it's a bad idea.
If the implementation is easy to explain, it may be a good idea.
Namespaces are one honking great idea -- let's do more of those!
description.782:

Members are professionals, students, consultants, enthusiasts and entrepreneurs who love data and understand the potential value it brings for society, business and government. Our regular event is the monthly Presentation series. This usually includes 1 longer talk (about 45 minutes) or two shorter talks (about 20 minutes). In lieu of speakers, we will have a lightening talk format welcoming anyone who wants to give a 5 to 15 minute talk.

  • The job must be available to someone living in the Gainesville area, meaning no relocation required. Remote is OK.

description.787:
OpenStack is a infrastructure as a service cloud platform that runs some of the worlds coolest private and public clouds. A user committee of over 5,600 active participants and 850 organizations makes OpenStack  the worlds largest open source project. OpenStack integrates with all major virtualization technologies including containers and is one of the few technologies that brings together database, storage, networking and security under the umbrella of the cloud. 

OpenStack has been embraced by the Enterprise, and companies like Walmart, IBM and Sony are just a few of the big brands that run their businesses with it. 

The project also has support from many of the worlds leading technology companies. Companies like Cisco, Google, Oracle, IBM, HP, VMware, RedHat, EMC, Canonical and others all have products, solutions and technology offerings built specifically for OpenStack. 

If you live in Central Florida and you interested in learning more abut OpenStack then you should definitely consider attending our user group to connect, learn and share ideas with some of the other stackers in Central Florida region. The user group meets once a month in downtown Orlando, and everyone is welcome from OpenStack Newbs to OpenStack Ninjas.

The meetup will be combination of education and discussions focused on the following; current OpenStack events, technical over views of OpenStack projects, installing and configuring the OpenStack Cloud, installing and configuring various OpenStack projects, OpenStack Architecture and implementations, and vendor presentations on OpenStack technologies and solutions.

description.844:
Every software engineer needs to practice. Born from the attendees of Code Retreat Boulder 2011, we meet bimonthly to hone our skills working on interesting problems.

The Code Retreat format was developed by Corey Haines and others. The essence of the format is that people pair-program on a problem for 45 minutes then throw away their code, take a short break, switch partners and repeat the process. Classically, these are full-day events including 6 programming sessions, a long lunch, and beer afterwards. In this group, we will meet in the evening and probably do just two sessions.

The primal Code Retreat problem is Conway's Game of Life - it's an interesting problem in that it admits a wide variety of solutions and is simple enough that one can usually almost (but not quite) write a complete implementation in 45 minutes. While we're starting off this group working on Life (at least for the first meetup) my hope is that we expand the scope to work on other problems of similar size, complexity, and that support a similar variety of approaches to their solution. Some possibilities include small parsers, interpreters, Project Euler problems, and other such challenges.

The official Code Retreat site can be found at http://coderetreat.com for more information.

description.888:
At KidsCanCode we make computers fun! By looking "under the hood," kids learn that a computer is a powerful tool - one they can use to create amazing projects of their own. Imagine building your own website, creating a video game, or wow-ing your teacher with an amazing science project. Our classes lay the foundation for a positive relationship with technology.

Benefits of learning programming

We are surrounded by technology, and every single piece of technology, from your smartphone to the car you drive, is controlled by software that was written by programmers. Learning about programming helps you learn about how computers work.

Developing programming skills, even at the elementary school level, can have numerous benefits:

  • It teaches about problem solving (algorithmic thinking)
  • It's cross-curricular (solve math problems or create an art project)
  • It generates early interest in Computer Science
  • It stimulates design & creativity
  • It strengthens math skills

What do we teach?

Python is a fully featured modern programming language that places an emphasis on writing code that is easy to read. As such, it has gained a strong following in educational circles as a first language for computer science courses.

A summary of Python's benefits:

  • It's Multi-platform - runs on all popular computing platforms.
    • If you're running Linux or OS X it's already installed!
  • It has wide global industry support.
    • Python is used at YouTube, NASA, Google, and many more large organizations you've heard of.
  • Clean and simple syntax.
  • General purpose - it can be applied to many different types of problems, from science to math to gaming and graphics.
  • Because of this, many colleges, such as MIT and several of the UC schools, have adopted Python for their introductory computer science classes.

New!  Scratch classes available for younger kids!

Scratch is a graphical educational programming environment specifically designed to teach programming concepts to younger children. By clicking together Lego-like blocks, kids can build up sequences of instructions to create animations, games, interactive stories, simulations, and more.

Scratch teaches many fundamental programming concepts such as iteration (looping), conditional statements, variables, threads, user interface design, event handling, and more.
description.889:
This is a language-agnostic group for developers, sysadmins and PMs to discuss the creation and consumption of RESTful web services. Let's get together and address the problems we all face regardless of the languages/frameworks we work in:

• How to structure our services

• What http status codes to use for various conditions

• How to handle sessions / user-logins / user-logouts

• Best practices for CORS and JSONP

• To force https or not?

• How to version an API and keep multiple versions running live

• How to test an API with SuperAgent, Postman, Curl, Selenium and others

• How to integrate Oauth

• How to write and generate documentation.

• How to deploy and/or integrate our API development into CI tools

Maybe this working group can set a unifying-standard for the creation of web services! And while we're at it, let's explore the various open apis available like Twilio, Twitter, AWS, and others. Let's consume as much as we create, and focus the discussions on the similarities between our implementations, instead of the differences.
