We help you to get the missing pieces your startup needs for the next level.

 

Go to http://socal106miles.launchrock.com/ and enter your email for future VIP event reminders


Our values are Reputation, Innovation, Solidarity, and Education.

 

This is our SoCal group; see also our Silicon Valley group.


Please join us if you're a founder or engineer (or friend!) and...

* You have worked at a startup,

* You want to work at a startup,

* You have started a company, and/or

* You want to start a company.

 

We meet several times a month (first Wednesday of each month in Palo Alto, 6-9pm; second Wednesday of the month in Redwood City, 6-9pm, and the last Wednesday of each month in San Francisco, 6-9pm; and now 3rd Wednesdays (or Thursdays) in Southern California).

* Socialize and learn from each other.

* Exchange ideas and information. Informally. Usually in a bar.

* Meet people at new startups.

* Meet people who want to work at startups.

 

106 Miles collaborates with Hackers & Founders for events like:

* Lean Startup: http://hackersandfounders.tv/e2N/eric-ries-the-lean-startup/

* Get Bigger: http://hackersandfounders.tv/key/get-bigger-with-vinod-khosla/

 

If you're curious to see what a 106 Miles meetup looks like, you can watch this video: http://youtu.be/4F1_o7CSWkM

 

Please follow us on Twitter, like us on Facebook, read our blog and 106miles.net ....
description.893: Meet other local Python developers, learners, and enthusiasts of all kinds. All skill levels are welcome. If you are interested in Python, we are interested in you!
description.894:
Tired of always being the only chick at tech meetups? Tired of for-profit girl-only meetups that cite feminist empowerment as a motivation to program? We started a hack for the ladies who want to keep it real. We don't want to hear about the glass ceiling. We don't want to be asked if our dad/brother/boyfriend got us into programming. We just want to get our hack on. GirlHack is every Thursday. Bring your latest project, bring a friend, bring your A-Game. 

We have 1weeks and 0weeks. 0weeks are are informal hacks: opportunities to pair, get feedback, or get help. 1weeks are hacks with a purpose, where we will be tackling specific topics, or hosting speakers. Occasionally, we'll host hikes, beach days, or even go rock climbing. And, tech conferences? Ooooh girl. Good times will be had by all. Location independent: We'll host in or around West LA / Santa Monica, until we find an optimal central location for our major patrons. (There's an algorithm for that!) 

We prefer to keep it open source. Our talks will probably never encompass Microsoft or Oracle technologies, due to cost (just like our meetups, we like our software FREE). Unix based operating systems are assumed (Linux, Mac, BSD). Let us know if you are a Windows user, hoping to come to the dark side. We have distros of Mint or Ubuntu waiting! UEFI notwithstanding. We're interested in: anything .js, ruby, php, python, functional, or c-based. We'll focus on: algorithms, version control, agile, TDD and BDD, workflow, frameworks, security, cryptography, maths, scientific programming, best practices, and more. 

It's all free, unless there are entry or venue fees. We want to keep this as free as possible. Girlhack has only one request: don't be a dick, and don't have one.
description.895:
This is a group for software developers, engineers, web devs, devops professional, administrators, startups, or anyone else interested in learning about the legalities of their work as they develop code. 

Most software engineers have a vague sense that they are involved in "intellectual property" generally, but they often don't fully understand the details. They also have a vague sense that the stuff they do involves some kind of law, but they aren't sure what or whether any of it makes sense.

In these meetups, we'll:

• host a (mostly) weekly virtual lunch meetup on what's going on in the world of software and law;

• occasionally have panels where lawyers and coders debate what happens when the worlds collide;

• have some basic instructional, "how to" sessions;

• talk a lot about open source and its legal and technical contours; but

• mostly, just have fun (I hope) debating all this stuff over lunch or happy hour.

About the Organizer, Michael Rice: I started this group because I'm a software engineer too. About eight years ago, I took a break and went to law school. Now I'm a part time lawyer, and I see a lot of developers either make mistake or shake their heads about it. Let's try to get some people together to talk about it -- and try to make sense of it all.
description.896:
This group was started to create a forum for experienced and aspiring web/mobile software entrepreneurs: product strategists, CTOs, hackers, CEOs, COOs, designers, developers/engineers, Scrum coaches, information architects, project managers, and more.

We will meet frequently to discuss the rapidly changing web/mobile consumer software space: 

- New technologies
- New apps!
- Cutting-edge hardware releases
- Startup process and incubation
- Open systems
- Development process efficiency/theory
- Idea iteration
- Business models
- Finance - friends/family to Venture Capital
- Product design and best practices

If you know any superstar entrepreneurs, please tell them about this group so we can build the most experienced group of software entrepreneurs in the area.


Keywords: android iphone sdk webos python django finance chief executive office cap table term sheet solr lucene apache cto ceo user interface experience agile scrum xp lean product development customer development customer discovery hadoop pig hive tableau zeromq venture php ruby rails nosql cassandra riak hbase mongodb node clojure
description.897:
Are you a Startup? Freelancer? Entrepreneur? Coder? Tired of working alone through the night? We've got you covered.

Twice a month, from 7pm - 12am, come to Coloft and work the night away in an inspiring, and creative atmosphere, around like-minded, ambitious people.

Who knows what can come out of this... the next billion-dollar idea perhaps? 

A $15 cover charge applies. Coloft members get priority registration and pay no cover.

Added Bonus: work space, wifi, super awesome people. 

p.s. Follow us on twitter @startupnights

p.p.s. Bring a laptop or something to work on.. this is a working/collaborating/strategizing/awesome night.

 

** In order to join this group, you must be approved. We want to make sure it grows organically... just like a startup.

 

*this is a Coloft event*
description.898:
This is a group for mid to senior Software Development professionals that have experience using Python and other open source technologies.

The goal of this meetup is to gather seasoned development professionals together to discuss using the latest web technologies to solve challenging problems, create innovative web applications from the ground up and understand exactly what it takes to create an outrageously good Web experience.
description.899: Want to learn how to make a web page, write an iPhone app, or program an Arduino? Here's your chance! Liberating Software, the Fresno Center for Open Software Literacy, is going to be holding regular "Coder Dojos", so bring your laptop and your ideas, and let's make them into something real.
description.900: Welcome! We are Coding Dojo, and this is our meetup for all people interested in web development. Coding Dojo is an Immersive Coding Bootcamp that teaches Five Full Stacks (LAMP, MEAN, Ruby on Rails, iOS, and Python). We host all different kinds of events related to the tech community. Join us for our next event!
description.901:
Fresno-Python's mission is to foster a welcoming and diverse community of Python developers and promote the use of the Python programming language in the Central Valley.

We're just getting going, and will have more information on upcoming meetups soon.

Stay tuned!
description.902:
How's your business or side project coming along?

Come join us for a healthy discussion of a dimension of startups that the Startup Tabloids rarely cover: Building a web product business without VC interference.

Maybe you are consultant or freelancer like us, sick of looking for client work and taking client calls. You'd rather be your own client, and build a product you own, that can bring real freedom to your worklife. We call it FREERlancing: You are free to decide how to build out your idea, and product income can mean you are free from hourly billing.

This is a group dedicated to exploring and learning, cross-polinating development, business, and marketing concepts. Ideas are cheap; we value great execution.

Whether you are a Ruby on Rails coder, a python/Django hacker, or prefer Java or .NET, come and pick up some tips on the business side to move your project forward.

Or maybe you have business in the works already, and are in need of learning some programming tricks to get it going? Come and see what magic others are bringing to life on the web.

Or perhaps you are just someone savvy enough to see all the money being made with web applications and info products, and are interested in starting a journey to financial independence. Welcome, kindred nerd! Share this journey with us.
description.903:
This is a meetup for systems administrators, data center operators, DevOps-minded folks, SaltStack customers, users and contributors. SaltStack is software used for enterprise scale infrastructure automation, cloud orchestration and application deployment and configuration management. The Salt open source software project is written in Python and according to GitHub is one of the largest and most active open source projects in the world. 
We will have Salt users/contributors sharing their use cases and how Salt solves real world business problems. Join us!
description.904: Just starting your first Angular tutorial? Come learn with us! We'll do our best to help you get all the directives, controllers, modules, and services, sorted out in no time. Already a pro Angler? Come teach us! Some of us still aren't quite clear on what a service is. Not interested in Angular at all, but looking for a place to come hack? You can come too, we'll make a convert of you yet!
description.905: Open to all interested in the intersection of Python and Data Science.
description.906:
PyData brings together both users and developers of data analysis tools to share ideas and learn from each other. The PyData community gathers to discuss how best to apply Python tools, as well as tools using R and Julia, to meet evolving challenges in data management, processing, analytics, and visualization. 

www.pydata.org
@PyData
description.907: Want to get started with Python? Looking for recommendations on books for beginners or methods? Looking for some folks to form a study group? Let's get together and share what we know.
description.908: This group is for developers and data scientists in Seattle who use data science and machine learning to build intelligent applications. Meetups will involve socializing & talks and some will be hands-on. We'll invite speakers to share their inspirational data products and intelligent apps and teach us how they did it. Join us!
description.909:
A monthly meetup of developers and hackers in Ventura County. All specialties, languages, and skillsets welcome!

See upcoming meetups here or at http://developers.vc, follow @vcdevelopers for brief updates, and subscribe to the low-volume spam free mailing list.
description.910:
This is a meetup focused on SDN technologies that are changing the networking industry, specifically the opensource Software-defined Networking controller OpenDaylight (ODL). ODL is developed by a consortium of companies (Intel, Cisco and Brocade to name a few) and managed by the Linux foundation. ODL is a versatile platform that is being deployed by companies like AT&T and Comcast to bring SDN and NFV benefits to a diverse set of networks. 

This is a group created for those interested in learning about, discussing and developing Software Defined Networking. The group is dedicated to fellow "future-casters" in the networking industry committed to innovation around next generation Open Access networks. 

Our events will be driven by the skill sets and interests of our members. If there's demand for basic "Introduction to OpenDaylight"-type events, we'll provide those. If people want to get some hands-on experience standing up and using OpenDaylight, we'll do that. If there's interest in taking a deeper dive into a feature of OpenDaylight, we can probably get the contributors who built that feature to join us, either remotely or in-person. If folks want help contributing to OpenDaylight, from improving a wiki to answering questions on ask.opendaylight.org to reporting bugs or writing code, we can get experienced community members to facilitate that process. 

Much like OpenDaylight and other Open Source projects, this community strives to be an open meritocracy. Have an idea for an event? We can facilitate it! Have some OpenDaylight experiences to share with the community? Let's make it happen!

Find more info on OpenDaylight at https://www.opendaylight.org/
ODL wiki https://wiki.opendaylight.org/
Checkout the code on github  https://github.com/opendaylight or ODL Gerrit https://git.opendaylight.org/gerrit
Get started using or developing for ODL at https://www.opendaylight.org/community-getting-started
description.911: We are a group of Systems Engineers and DevOps folks who want to Ansible all the things. Want to learn more about Ansible? Come join us. Already know Ansible well? Come share your knowledge.
description.912: This is a meetup for Vancouver users of Spark (http://spark.apache.org), the high-speed cluster programming framework. We'll also discuss other Spark-related projects, including Spark SQL, MLlib, GraphX and Spark Streaming. The meetup includes introductions to the various Spark features, case studies from users, best practices for deployment and tuning, and updates on development.
description.913: Come to meet people from the local software development industry. We'll share tips and stories and find out who's doing what in Vancouver and the Lower Mainland. Make those network contacts that are so essential in our careers. Regular meetings open with a short technical presentation to kick off our discussions. Then, following Q&A and possibly a door prize draw, we have our round-the-room introductions and open networking. For the introductions we invite all participants to introduce themselves and to let us know what they'd like to talk with others about. This is when connections are made so think about what you would like to say beforehand, especially if speaking in front of a group seems difficult. Social meetings skip the presentation and round-the-room introductions and jump right in to open networking, possibly with a door prize draw. We often invite special guests such as recruiters and speakers so that you have a chance to meet them face-to-face. Of course our "network" is about more than just our meetings. Beyond our members' personal networks we have an opt-in mailing list plus our groups on LinkedIn, Facebook, and Yahoo! See our About Us page at http://softwaredev.meetup.com/17/about/ for more details.
description.914:
Hi Vancouver Djangonauts!

Django is a Python web framework that encourages rapid development and clean, pragmatic design. With comprehensive documentation and a strong and helpful community behind it, Django enables the development of high-performing web applications in less time, using less code.

The purpose of this meetup group is to share experiences in developing, deploying and scaling Django applications. Our meetups are casual and friendly. All levels of experience with Django are welcome, so whether you're interested in learning to deploy Django for the first time, or you've been tracking trunk since 0.90, then come on down!
description.915:
The goal of the Santa Barbara Data Science Meetup is to gather professionals, academics, and practitioners around problems concerning the acquisition, analysis, and visualization of data---something that has been recently deemed the sexiest job of the century.

This group is meant to complement the excellent Santa Barbara R Users Group, with the goal to extend its audience beyond R users.

Initially, the meetup will follow the steps, and topics, of more established groups with a similar focus, possibly by drawing from the same pool of speakers.

In the lulls between meetups and Kaggle competitions a fresh source of data-related buzz can be found on the newborn DataTau.
description.916: This is a group for those interested in learning more about MongoDB!
description.917: Group for Django and Python developers, professionals, and enthusiasts. Python is a beautiful language and Django is a smart and powerful framework. This group allows experts to share their knowledge and passion while those new to Django or Python can develop. I would like to develop my skills and knowledge, help others (if I can), and help grow the development in and near Sacramento.
description.918: We are a group of Systems Engineers and DevOps folks who want to Ansible all the things. Want to learn more about Ansible? Come join us. Already know Ansible well? Come share your knowledge.
description.919:
South County Web Developers is a study group for web designers and developers of all skill levels to get together, work on some cool websites, make friends, network, learn some of the hottest frameworks, and have fun!

Mission

This group aims to become a motivated and driven web design/development community within and near the Morgan Hill area. Some of our key initiatives are, but may not be limited to:

• To connect together web designers/developers within the Morgan Hill area 
• To provide resources for designers/developers to learn and improve skills
• To provide a friendly, learning and collaborative environment for designers/developers to jump-start and work on website projects alongside each other
• To help aspiring designers/developers discover a passion in the technology field 

All aspiring designers/developers are welcome! Bring your laptop to events, and tell your friends about our group!

Join our Facebook group here: https://www.facebook.com/groups/GilroyMorganHillWebDevelop...
description.920:
Let's get together and practice competitive programming!

Nearly all competitive programming happens in online communities (HackerRank, TopCoder, CodeEval, CodeForces, SPOJ etc). But I wonder if there is enough interest to do the same thing in a room i.e. sitting  around a table, pretty much like a LAN party.

Would it be fun? Would it be faster learning? Can we take defeat sportingly? How far can we go?
description.921:
We are a group for female developers Silicon Valley area. All who identify as women are welcome!

Developers and aspiring developers only, please! No recruiters, except for sponsors.

Please check out our Facebook page:

https://www.facebook.com/groups/svpyladies/

We are looking for sponsors, so if you are interested, please let us know!
description.922: This group is for Python Programming Workshops and Study Groups. We are a group of engineers from various tech companies in the Bay Area helping to organize these workshops and grow the Python community.
description.923:
We are Alglorist Coders.

We bring glory to the ancient subject of Algorithm Design by using it to build software.

We are a real life, face-to-face technical community of  computer  programmers interested in Algorithm Design who get together at Hacker Dojo in Mountain View to talk, listen, and  socialize discussing practical algorithms for solving problems all around us.

Our goal is to help coders in  high level languages like Python,  C++, or Java to acquire algorithm design skills as well as verbal exposition skills.

We are Alglorist Coders. We use Math and Logic-based Globish  to communicate with one another. We welcome all accents and all unconventional sentence  styles  that convey the Algorithmic essence of the topic under discussion.

Alglore is folklore of Algorithm Designers and that is a good way to get  some of the best of the past of humankind. Logical argument inherent in the folklore is really the focus of this group.

We model our argumentation style emulating W Richard Stark's 1990 book "LISP, Lore, and Logic An Algebraic View of LISP Programming, Foundations, and Applications"

What do we mean by Performant High level Code?

Performant code runs on current hardware to provide adequate fast response to end users. Our belief is that performant code can be written in mainstream high level languages like Ecmascript, Python, Java, Scala, Clojure, C++ etc. We can implement innovative ideas in software if we are aware of the pitfalls of the past attempts acknowledging all that is good in the current state of the art. 

We conduct low priced code-intensive workshops in mainstream high level languages to enhance implementation skills of algorithm designers and working programmers.

Please join us and help us build a community of highly motivated coders interested in continual learning!

We learn from the past and act in the present to build a better future.
description.924:
Welcome to the official RethinkDB Bay Area meetup group! RethinkDB is an open-source, distributed database, built to store JSON documents at scale.

Come meet the RethinkDB team, learn how to build better apps with existing and upcoming features, and get one-on-one support from fellow RethinkDB users and makers at the office hours.

Let's learn, teach, and build software together!
description.925:
This purpose of this group is to bring together a group of people with Asperger's/autism and provide mutual support in navigating the tech industry.

All aspects of technology are included: programming, data entry, data science, hardware, operating systems, office software, computer art and graphic design, industrial design, engineering, mathematics, science, electronics, startups, space exploration, testing, entrepreneurship, hackerspaces, and much more.

No previous experience with technology is required -- just a desire to learn and help others. Complete beginners are welcome. Those with experience can provide advice and support to the newcomers.

More information will be posted here soon.

FAQs

Do I need any experience with technology?
All levels of experience are welcome, including complete beginners.

What is the format of the meetings?
I think that this group will start with online discussions and move towards some in-person meetings after that. I’m also looking for assistance with planning the format of this group, so please email me if you have suggestions or would like to assist. If you prefer to participate only via the Internet, then you can do so in the discussion forum (coming soon).

Why tech?
There is a large tech scene in the Bay Area and it's the field that I'm familiar with. Some tech companies, like SAP and Microsoft, have programs to actively seek out employees with autism/Asperger's, and that's the niche that this group focuses on. According to one source, "the unemployment rate for people with Asperger's is as high as 85 percent", so maybe this group can target that problem. If we are successful with this group that targets the tech industry, maybe other similar groups could be formed to support people who are interested in other fields.

I’m not technical, but I’m a tech entrepreneur with autism/Asperger’s -- can I still join?
Yes, everyone is welcome.

Are there good resources for learning how to program?
I'm working on this and will post a list of resources soon. Sign up for this meetup group or the email newsletter to be notified when it's ready.

I am the parent of a child with autism/Asperger’s -- can I join?
Yes.

Do I need an official autism or Asperger’s diagnosis to join? 
An official diagnosis is not required. This is an inclusive and friendly group for people who are interested in helping each other.

Are there other meetup groups about Asperger's and autism?
Yes, click here for a list.

Can I register on the meetup page with a pseudonym?
Yes, anonymity is fine. Meetup doesn't show information about the group to non-members.

Is there a website?
There will be one here soon.

If I contribute money with the "chip in" feature, what does the money go towards?
Meetup fees, web hosting for the future website, a discussion forum, and other costs associated with running the group. Contact me if you have questions.

Can I sponsor your group?
Yes. Any assistance with organization, meeting space, software, hardware, partnerships, job training, and/or other help would be greatly appreciated. Please contact the organizers. 

Where can I send additional questions and feedback about the group?
Click here to send me an email.

More information will be posted here soon.
description.926: This group is for anyone interested in computer programming. Python is one of the top ranking programming languages. All skill levels are welcome. Basic purpose is to get exposure of python from smart people all over the world. We can also meet at some restaurant for some food and drink afterward. Let's meetup and share knowledge.
description.927: This is a group for Russian Speaking Hackers and Developers from the Bay Area and SF. We meet to hack on new technologies, discuss best practices, startup news, talk about our side projects. Join and tell what are you working on!
description.928: Meet other local users of one of  open source database products. Learn about different MySQL products and share your experience. Everyone, of all knowledge levels is welcome!
description.929: We are the Bay Area Python Interest Group. No membership is required, and beginners are welcome!
description.931: Open to all interested in the intersection of Python and Data Science.
description.932:
This group was formed to motivate and support individuals who want to learn a computer programming language, who have little to no coding experience, and who live in Oakland. 

Members study at their own pace and learn coding utilizing freely available online materials. We help members to stay on course and progress by facilitating study circles, pairing, and group discussions. 

We explore and discuss practical applications for developing your programming skills. We are passionate about helping to nurture individuals with technological skills from within the Oakland community. We want to do our part in facilitating opportunities for Oaklanders to create technology, instead of only consuming it.

Our meetup group is comprised of experienced coders as well as newbies, and features more than just the HTML/CSS popular in beginning "programming" meetups. 

We meet at Oakland’s original technology hotspot and salon, Tech Liminal in downtown Oakland. Check it out and join us! http://techliminal.com

--

If you would like to facilitate a study circle or organize a meeting, please email the meetup organizer and we'll get you listed on the site.  Or, if you have an event or workshop located in Oakland, we are happy to list it, provided you are not charging for your meetup.
description.933: This is a group for anyone interested in programming. That's right! Whether you a professional, amateur, student, senior, junior, women, or men as long as you're interested, passionate, and live and breathe in programming ; you're all welcome. Basically, this group will meet once a month (the more the better) to talk about the current news or project in web design, developer, etc. Member will be able to share their project while others will be able to express an opinion. We could also do a get together meetup where we all can code and help each other. Or, we could even just get dinner together and share experiences in tech. I really hope that this meetup will promote and encourage more programmers in the area to get together and build a better, stronger, tech community in Monterey.
description.934: The Quant Club is for anyone interested in quantitative finance and machine learning. We are a rather informal meetup for new and experienced Quants. We organize meetings where we share tips how to build trading systems using machine learning and other techniques.
description.935:
Meet others in the San Francisco Bay Area interested in Hierarchical Temporal Memory (HTM). 
HTM is a new computing paradigm that replicates the structure and function of the human neocortex.
Join this group to help you understand HTM and begin building intelligent systems.
description.936: Interested in the Dropbox Platform? Stop by to learn more about the Dropbox APIs and meet other developers working with the platform. Great talks, good food and drinks, and maybe some fun too.
description.937:
N.E.R.D.S (New Erudite Recursive DNS Symposium) is a ~monthly event hosted in our Gandi offices in SF.

We're into domain names and the magnificent system we call [the] DNS. We love and hate DNSSEC. We love and hate the new gTLDs. We can `dig` faster than the speed of light. We laugh in the face of propagation. We know what ports 43 and 53 are for, and furthermore, we hack our own scripts to `whois` more efficiently (and colorfully). We like rainbows and ponies and DNS ASCII art too.

At these events, we will discuss all things related to domains, including but not limited to new gTLDs, zone files, records and DNS, hosting and VPS, ICANN rules, privacy and security, our CLI and APIs \o/.
description.938: Come visit us at our downtown office and check out what's in alpha, beta, and let us help you with building your apps.
description.939:
We're going to run some introductory machine learning and data science courses. These are all going to be targeted to experienced software engineers who just want to learn more about machine intelligence. In all of this, we're assuming that you probably know how to read software manuals, but the barrier to understanding state of the art machine learning is just a bit higher than is easy to pull off on evenings and weekends. So we'll focus on helping you to develop intuition and a good, solid understanding of the basics as well as enough software to help you keep going when you get home (or back to work). In other words, we'll help you decide what to do next.

In the process, we'd like to help people get to know each other.

(There's no monopoly here on actually doing the courses or trainings. If you think you'd like to offer ML/DS instruction, ping the organizer and we can schedule something.)

The world does not lack in free online courses and articles on ML and DS, of course. This works for some, not for all. And for many of us who work with these topics, it's easy to forget that it can be hard at first.

If anyone here wants to use this meetup to propose introductory courses to help people get up to speed, feel free to ping me and I'm happy for this group to serve as a vehicle. If you have ideas on how to make such courses better find their audiences, that's also a useful topic. Based on the profiles of those who have joined the meetup, we're perhaps a group that mostly understands ML and DS rather than a group at the beginning of the adventure.
description.940:
We're a bunch of hackers who are excited about building apps on Yo - world's most simple & powerful API.

We meetup on a bi-weekly basis at the Yo HQ to work on and teach others how to build mind-blowing apps. 

Bonus

When you join you will receive the most coveted swag in the Silicon Valley, our official Yo T-Shirt. 

P.S. we'll always have coffee and ping pong available.
description.941:
Hack, plot and hang out with the Disqus team and other Disqus users and developers.

Connect with us on Twitter & Facebook:

@Disqus
 @DisqusCode
 Disqus on Facebook
description.942: Meet others interested in developing apps on Google App Engine. This meetup has a strong programming focus, so talks showing working code and workarounds are actively encouraged. Each meetup will have a reasonable amount of time for informal lightning talks to show members' work.
description.943:
We like scaling big systems, do you?

ArchCamp is a meetup for engineers, by engineers. The goal is to talk about building systems (often at high scale) without having to listen to any sales pitches.

 

Event format:

20 min - mingle & discussion about the last event

40 min - lightning talks 5 minutes. (laptop setup is on your time, not ours)

60 min - open discussion about the topic du jour

We have a meetup every 4 to 6 weeks

 

The cornerstone event for this meetup is the ArchCamp unconference. We are aiming to to this four or five times a year with smaller events in between.
description.944: Millions of users listen to Spotify's streaming music service world wide. Behind the scenes is a world class technology organization that innovates hard to make the music easy. This Meetup is devoted to exploring how Spotify's technology stack works and to the hackers who use Spotify's APIs. We'll get together to meet both Spotify engineers and business leaders and anyone who takes the time to do something cool with Spotify's APIs.
description.945: Join our meetup group for events centered around building with Twilio cloud communications, design and development, APIs, and more.
description.946:
ChatOps, a term coined by GitHub, is an approach to managing technical and business operations through a group chat room. ChatOps San Francisco is for the discussion and collaboration on all aspects of ChatOps including tools, security, and methodology.

Events will include one or two presentations of up to 30 minutes each, plus extra time for networking and chatting, or maybe even a little pair programming. If you're interested in speaking at an event or hosting an event, please get in touch using the "contact" button in the "organizers" section of the left sidebar. Topics that are appropriate for the group are anything directly or tangentially related to using a group chat as the interface for automation, workflows, team building, etc.

The talks generally require a basic understanding of ChatOps, so if you are just learning about the idea, it would be useful to do a little reading or watch a video or two before attending your first meetup. Some good resources to get started:

• ChatOps at Github, the first public talk on the subject by Jesse Newland

• The Rise of ChatOps, from our first meetup

• /r/chatops, a subreddit with articles and discussion

The presentations at each meetup are live streamed and posted to the ChatOps San Francisco YouTube channel afterwards. Be sure to check out the channel for all the great presentations from past meetups!
description.947:
If you've ever visited Hacker News, you've almost certainly seen the "Show HN" or "Ask HN" posts. Well, it's time to get off the Internet and tell us about it face to face. We'll provide you with our honest feedback, you provide us with a great hack, or idea. We'll give you 5 minutes to show off your tool, hack, library, whatever.

We're language and software/hardware agnostic, so it's all fair game. After you present, it's an open forum. The audience will ask questions and provide feedback. We want to enable as much participation as possible at these meetups, so you'd better be able to take criticism and dish it out (all within reason of course).
description.948:
Hackers + Designers + Entrepreneurs = Code Crew!

Passionate about learning how to code, creating beautiful designs or building the prototype for your business idea and tired of doing it alone? Then this is the group for you!

This is the perfect group for people serious about learning how to code through self-study using resources on the web like Code School, Codecademy, Treehouse, P2PU, Coursera, edX, Udacity, programming books, screencasts or whatever else is out there on the internet. We also share a helpful suggested reading on our blog and issue occasional code challenges. If you're just starting out and want to get a head start then check out some cool resources here.

We are a group of software engineers, designers and entrepreneurs that enjoy building cool stuff with code at our collaborative coding/pair programming sessions. We currently have members building with HTML, CSS, Javascript, Ruby, Ruby on Rails, Python, Django, PHP, Objective C and more. So come join us and meet some cool and interesting people while picking up a new skill!
description.949: This is a group for developers who want to learn more about building web applications using the Nitrous cloud-based IDE
description.950:
A meetup for Twisted Python developers.

If you are interested in event-driven networking in Python, come to learning sessions and sprints to see what Twisted is all about.

If you already use Twisted, come to the sprints and and fix some bugs/add new features!

http://twistedmatrix.com
description.951: A meetup for people who continuously deploying websites and apps, to show stories from high seas of software development and best tools to ship quality code.
description.952: Hack nights are a great way for developers in the Python community to get to know one another, to find out about new and interesting projects, and to generally get the pulse of the community. Whether you're working on the latest bits of Open Source greatness or planning the application that's going to win you the world, the SF Python Hack Night can provide you with valuable early feedback. Plus, it's fun! Who wouldn't want to hack some Python over beer and pizza?
description.953: Join other fellow Python hackers in San Francisco for drinks.
description.954: Where thought leaders in software development share their stories. At the Atlassian Dev Den, you’ll learn about smashing successes, epic fails, and lessons learned. Meet other software pros and swap your own stories over free beer, wine, and food.
description.955: We're a group that uses hacking, stats, and machine learning to dig up alpha in the financial markets. Programmers, traders, and everyone else who enjoys crunching numbers is welcome to contribute and work on ideas.
description.956: This meetup is for everyone from Spree experts all the way to those investigating Spree. No other platform will offer you the same degree of control and ownership as Spree Commerce. With our technology, you can take COMMAND of your own destiny while standing out in a competitive retail environment. We want to make sure you get the most out of Spree from both a development and store-owner perspective. During these demos, we will do live demos, talks about Spree extensions and integrations people are building, talk about projects they have completed, allow people to share war stories and create opportunities to collaborate.
description.957: Calling all Mercurial users! This is a group for anyone interested in learning more about Mercurial and to see where it's heading.
description.958: We discuss object-oriented programming from a dogmatic and radical point of view, called "Object Thinking"
description.959: Interested in healthcare? Bummed out by the bad software and UI made my most healthcare companies? We're a group of designers, engineers, and healthcare experts looking to change that. Join us!
description.960: This group is for developers and data scientists in the Bay Area who use data science and machine learning to build intelligent applications. Meetups will involve socializing & talks and some will be hands-on. We'll invite speakers to share their inspirational data products and intelligent apps and teach us how they did it. Join us!
description.961:
Escape from /dev/null (or just /dev/null for short) is series of unique and engaging programming competitions.

Actually, they differ from traditional programming competitions in that they are not boring, not about boring things, mostly shy away from abstract algorithmic brain-twisters and instead focus on practicality and having fun.

The 'outer game' is played by logging int to a web-based interface. It could theoretically be played online entirely, but it's always done in a ballroom setting where all players as teams and the judges meet in person during the game.

The 'inner game' is revealed one challenge at a time where teams create their own way of interacting with it.
description.962: Calling all coders that love to discuss computer language design and implementation!  Whether you're functional, imperative, or declarative come hang out for open discussion, lightning talks, and some formal talks. Meet other language geeks and get some socialization!  Experts and beginners are welcome.  You might learn, teach, eat, or drink something. Your fearless leader is all around nice guy and supreme dictator for life Terence Parr, The ANTLR and StringTemplate Guy.  I will moderate the discussions to avoid too many food fights and dampen non-Terence loudmouths.  Interest level will dictate location in San Francisco (e.g., coffee shop, bar, university lecture room, industry meeting room, etc...).  For fun, I might even take the show on the road to tech spots like Seattle, Bangalore, or Superman's hideout at the North Pole.
description.963: Meet the Stripe team and members of the Stripe community.
description.964: The Ladies in Tech Social Club is a fun place to meet and find friends in the tech community. The aim of the club is to build friendships and a strong community around like minded people. Come join us for happy hour after work or participate on the weekend with trips to the beach, movies or any other fun we can think up.
description.965: CodeClass.io offer coding and technical workshops to help you get a jump start on your learning. We are a group of passionate developers, hackers, builders who love to learn and teach.
description.966: Creating good data viz isn't as simple as throwing pixels up onto a screen. Here we'll talk about everything from rendering SVG objects, to acquiring and organizing data, to libraries for displaying information. This is about the merging of design, front end coding skills, and all things data.
description.967: A series of talks and workshops bringing together the best minds in Data Science in the Bay Area, hosted in the beautiful OpenTable Offices.
description.968:
Este grupo es un lugar para que desarrolladores aprendan más acerca de MongoDB la base de datos no-relacional, open source y basada en documentos. MongoDB está cambiando la forma como los desarrolladores construyen aplicaciones y tiene una comunidad que crece cada vez más en el mundo entero. Si estas enfrentando desafíos con MySQL, Postgres u Oracle y quieres explorar la productividad, la facilidad de uso y la escalabilidad, entre otras características únicas que MongoDB ofrece; ¡Únete con nosotros! y vive una de nuestras sesiones mensuales. Y si tienes alguna experiencia con MongoDB para compartir, ¡Háznoslo saber!, ¡Estaremos encantados de conocerte!

English Version:
This group is a place for developers to learn more about the non-relational, open source, document database MongoDB. MongoDB is changing the way developers build applications and has built a thriving global community that you can join. If you are facing challenges with MySQL or Postgres or Oracle and want to explore MongoDB’s developer productivity, ease of use and scalability, please join us at one of our monthly sessions. If you have MongoDB experience to share, let us know! We would love to have you present!
description.969: Este grupo es para aquellos interesados en el software CG-UNO, creado por la compañia Sistemas de Informacion. Aqui nos ayudaremos a resolver problemas comunes que tengamos, y a sugerir configuraciones que han sido exitosas. La idea tambien es crear un grupo de amigos con intereses comunes.
description.970:
Django Cali es una comunidad creada con el objetivo de agrupar a todos los interesados en el framework de desarrollo Django, esto para conocer personas, compartir ideas, crear proyectos, aprender y pasar un rato agradable con personas con los mismos intereses.

El objetivo final es  permitir a los integrantes, aprender sobre este framework que permite desarrollar productos mínimos viables para poder validar tus ideas en el mercado.
description.971: Este es un grupo para todos aquellos programadores y principiantes en programación que deseen aportar al desarrollo web con Javascript, HTML5 y todos los frameworks relacionados con estas tecnologias que sean tema de discusion en el grupo y generen contenido libre y de calidad
description.972: Meetup de la ciudad de Pasto que busca compartir conocimiento sobre los temas de desarrollo Web y Móvil
description.973: Grupo de desarrolladores en Python, apasionados por el lenguaje y con ganas de aprender cada dia
description.974: Este grupo tem o objetivo de unir e fortalecer a comunidade Gamer de Santarém. Com espaço para artistas, programadores ou qualquer apaixonado por jogos que sonha em criá-los ou simplesmente jogá-los!!
description.975:
Welcome, Ansible friend!

We believe that Ansible is the best tool around for the automation of systems management tasks.  We gather periodically to share knowledge, best practices, and opportunities around Ansible.

We're always looking for potential speakers or hosts for our Ansible meetups. If you'd like to talk about how you're using Ansible, or if you'd like to volunteer space for an upcoming meetup, please contact one of the organizers from the meetup's main page.
description.976:
B.L.T. stands for Build, Learn and Teach.

OSS stands for Open Source Software.

B.L.T. OSS is a hackaton for helping people to understand and contribute back to the open source software ecosystem.

Together we can build a better OSS community in Dublin. 

You can join our SLACK channel here.

Please checkout our Code of Conduct if you would like to attend.

Everybody is welcome!

Your level of software development skills does not matter, what matters is the desire to learn new things.
description.977:
Welcome to OpenStack Ireland

The mission of the OpenStack community is to produce the ubiquitous open source cloud computing platform. By being easy to implement and massively scalable, this platform will meet the needs of both public cloud providers and enterprises deploying private clouds. Launched with code contributions from Rackspace and the NASA Nebula cloud platform, OpenStack is now supported by numerous technology leaders.
description.978:
Follow us!

Facebook Group: WWCode Dublin

Twitter: @WWCodeDublin #wwcode #wwcdublin

Mission:

Women Who Code is a global nonprofit organization dedicated to inspiring women to excel in technology careers by creating a global, connected community of women in technology. The organization tripled in 2013 and has grown to be one of the largest communities of women engineers in the world.

Empowerment:

Women Who code is a professional community for women in tech. We provide an avenue for women to pursue a career in technology, help them gain new skills and hone existing skills for professional advancement, and foster environments where networking and mentorship are valued.

Key Initiatives:

Free technical study groups

Events featuring influential tech industry experts and investors

Hack events

Career and leadership development

Current and aspiring coders are welcome. 

Bring your laptop and a friend! 

Support Women Who Code:

Donating to Women Who Code, Inc. (#46-4218859) directly impacts our ability to efficiently run this growing organization, helps us produce new programs that will increase our reach, and enables us to expand into new cities around the world ensuring that women and girls everywhere have the opportunity to pursue a career in technology.

Women Who Code (WWCode) is dedicated to providing an empowering experience for everyone who participates in or supports our community, regardless of gender, gender identity and expression, sexual orientation, ability, physical appearance, body size, race, ethnicity, age, religion, or socioeconomic status. Because we value the safety and security of our members and strive to have an inclusive community, we do not tolerate harassment of members or event participants in any form. Our Code of Conduct applies to all events run by Women Who Code, Inc. If you would like to report an incident or contact our leadership team, please submit an incident report form.

WomenWhoCode.com

Twitter | Facebook
description.979:
Zalando is Europe's leading online fashion platform for men, women and children. The +800 members of Zalando's tech team are passionate about the work we do and the technologies we use to get things done, and we love to share our enthusiasm with the rest of the world. Join our Meetup group to receive news about the technical talks, workshops, and other events that we host at our Barrow Street office. 

Some of the topics and technologies that our team and guest speakers are likely to talk about: Machine Learning, Data Mining, Big Data, Python, Open-Source, Data Visualization, Recommender Systems, PostgreSQL, APIs, agile development and methodologies and women in tech. Sure, that's a long list--but Zalando is quite a complex operation! We use all of the above and more to create the best customer experiences for our +16 million users. 

Hope to see you at an upcoming meetup. Meantime: 

• Visit our tech blog for more info on Zalando's tech operations and team

• Follow us on Twitter, Instagram, Facebook and Google+
description.980: "VFX Ireland is a community forum for Irish VFX practitioners and students. A place to share VFX news, tips & tricks, tutorials, events etc." This group is to arrange informal meetups, each one focusing on a theme in VFX, but also just a means for us to get to know each other and keep in touch. I hope to have a recurring monthly meetup, and perhaps random one-off events too. As the VFX industry goes, Ireland is relatively isolated. I think this makes it all the more important we meet up! I'm looking forward to attending events created by our members :) Join the facebook group https://www.facebook.com/VfxIreland
description.981: We are a group of Systems Engineers and DevOps folks who want to Ansible all the things. Want to learn more about Ansible? Come join us. Already know Ansible well? Come share your knowledge.

Every month we meet up in order to practice code katas, clean code, software craftsmanship, pair programming, Test-Driven Development and learn from each other for an hour or two. As it's after work, food and drinks are provided :)

If you'd like to learn more about Software Craftsmanship, the best place to start is 'What Is Software Design?' by Jack Reeves (use Google). If you'd like more in-depth material, Pete McBreen's Book: 'Software Craftsmanship: the new imperative' is great start.
description.983:
If you are interested in the Python Programming language, this group is for you. The idea is to learn from one another and pick the brains of any experienced Python programmer we can find. We intend to generally have fun building things with Python. All skill levels are welcome. Looking forward to doing cool things with everybody.

Check our website http://www.pythonaberdeen.org
description.984:
Éste es el Meetup Group para la comunidad de usuarios de MongoDB en el Perú.

MongoDB, nombre que proviene de "humongous" ("descomunal" en inglés). Aquí se abordará casi todo relacionado con el banco de datos NoSQL MongoDB: instalación, exploración, desarrollo, mantenimiento, etc.

description.986: Django Girls es una organización sin fines de lucro que capacita y ayuda a las mujeres a organizarse, talleres gratuitos de programación de un día al proporcionar herramientas, recursos y apoyo. Nació en julio de 2014 en Berlín y comenzó por dos Olas: Sitarska y Sendecka. Hoy en día, Django Girls es una organización dirigida por voluntarios con cientos de personas que contribuyen a atraer a más mujeres a Python y Django comunidad. description.987: This is a community for all those interested in Data Science. We exist to bring together the diverse range of people that work in the industry and create opportunities for knowledge sharing, collaboration and exploration of this rapidly advancing and fascinating field. Whether you are a fully fledged data geek or simply someone with an interest in Big Data there will be something here for you.
description.988: This is a group dedicated to the tools and techniques required to be effective with Data Driven decision making. It's about lowering the bar to entry. It's dedicated to creating a support network within the area that turns Manchester into a Data Driven Techniques hot bed. description.990: We are a group of Systems Engineers and DevOps folks who want to Ansible all the things. Want to learn more about Ansible? Come join us. Already know Ansible well? Come share your knowledge.
description.991:
This is a group for anyone interested in software development with the Pyramid Web framework.

The purpose of the group is to discuss best practice, usage patterns, problems and solutions.

All with interest in Pyramid are welcome, no matter if you've just started or have been using it for years, or coming from a different framework and want to learn what all the fuss is about.

description.993:
This is a group for people who love working with data. We are open to data scientists, engineers, hackers and and enthusiasts, and would love to see the community grow in Lisbon.


No advanced knowledge of Machine Learning is required, though knowing (at least basic) python is necessary. Many things are going to be based on scikit and pandas, but all are welcome.


We focus on two types of events, most of which will be at Startup Lisboa (Rua da Prata):

(1) Meetups where data scientists do short (under 10 minute) talks about tools or techniques that might be useful, and where the most common tools are explored. The objective is also for everyone to meet, have a beer, and discuss ideas.  These will be held on workdays, after work hours.

(2) Weekend mini-hackathons where we for teams and go straight into the data, using public data sources such as Dados.gov, Kaggle.com or Pordata.
description.994:
The Lisbon MongoDB User Group is a place for developers and DB admins to learn more about the non-relational, open source, document-oriented database MongoDB.

MongoDB is the leading NoSQL database and many of the key committers often travel to Europe. So if you are facing challenges with MySQL, Postgres or Oracle, and would like to explore a more flexible, scalable alternative, please join us at one of our friendly, periodical sessions in Lisbon.
description.995: This is the Python Users Group Lisbn. We host presentations and discussions about Python and Python-related software development (mostly framework-independent). Our talks are mostly done in english You might also want to subscribe to our mailing list which is our actual home.
description.996: The Apache Cassandra Project develops a highly scalable second-generation distributed database, bringing together Dynamo's fully distributed design and Bigtable's ColumnFamily-based data model. The Lisbon Apache Cassandra User Group is a highly awesome meetup group, bringing together cool people distributed across Lisbon to talk about our favorite NoSQL implementation, Apache Cassandra.
description.997: We are a group of Systems Engineers and DevOps folks who want to Ansible all the things. Want to learn more about Ansible? Come join us. Already know Ansible well? Come share your knowledge.
description.998: Leicester Data Hacking and Visualization Meetup is a community of people interested in manipulating data and visualization. We explore the full range of techniques for converting raw data into visible, shareable insights. We use techniques like scripting languages to collect and manipulate data. Representing data in databases (big or small), several of which are schema-less (NoSQL), or even in files from plain old CSV to those stored across large clusters. Feel free to participate if you are out to start learning, or a long time data miner (before it was even called data science). Your interest in data could be from open government, through business insights, to scientific computing. It could just be putting information on a timeline, showing connections or creating graphics purely for their aesthetics via very simple algorithms.
description.999: Events for Oxonians who like to build projects with Raspberry Pi.
description.1000: This group is for anyone interested in Tech be that Web Development, Data Visualization, Python programming, UI, Big Data, IoT design or any related field. It is for people who dont mind looking out of their own box and learning new things and mingling with people of a similar bent. I envisage this group to be one of tutorials, guest speakers and free food. Most of all it is to be community led. So if you have an experience that you wish to share or a starter lesson you would like to give then feel to step up and make a suggestion. I am also looking for co-organisers so please contact me if any of this interests you.
description.1001:

Passionate about learning how to code, creating beautiful designs or building the prototype for your business idea and tired of doing it alone? Then this is the group for you!

description.1002: Meet the Stripe team and members of the Stripe community in London.
description.1003: A group of like-minded Business & IT experts interested networking, meeting other specialists in the market and discussing all topics related to Financial Services and technologies such as Hadoop, Spark, Cassandra, MongoDB, Scala, Python, Qlikview, Spotfire and Tableau.
description.1004:
DevOps Enthusiasthas been set up by Arrows Group due to the vast expansion of DevOps in the industry…!

With the increase in the terminology, methodology and corresponding technologies of DevOps, it seems to be different for each organisation and person doing ‘DevOps’.

These events will have 2-3 guest speakers, speaking about their methods of DevOps, what has worked for them, what has not, any challenges they have had and so on... It is a great way to mingle with other DevOps Enthusiasts within London and surrounding areas as well!


Interested in speaking, submitting ideas or anything else - contact devops@arrowsgroup.com
description.1005:
Note: chat with the London Community 24/7: 

http://slock.it:3000 then join channel #ethereum_london

Ethereum is a platform and programming language that makes it possible for any developer to build and publish next-generation decentralized applications. In short: Ethereum is the web, without the web servers.

Ethereum can be used to codify, decentralize, secure and trade just about anything: voting, domain names, financial exchanges, crowdfunding, company governance, contracts and agreements of most kind, intellectual property, and even smart property thanks to hardware integration.
description.1006: This group is for sharing knowledge and asking question on everything tech and start up related. It's about socializing in informal atmosphere, but at the same time learning something new. If you work Tech, or plan to make a start up - you might want to learn some basics about different technologies or different aspects of a Tech Start Up. Some simple knowledge you take for granted in your everyday job might be new and interesting to the rest of us. May be you are thinking about starting a tech start up, but not sure if your idea even makes sense from technological point of view? My be you are a developer, but you've never worked with UI, and before signing for any courses, you want to get some basic idea on what is it about? Or may be you are a graphical designer, who considers starting making apps, but is not sure, if coding is really for them? Or just want to meet interesting people that are involved or are interested in the London Tech scene! Please join this meet up, and come to the meetings, it's going to be fun!
description.1007: This group has been set up to bring together the XMPP/realtime community in London.
description.1008:
This is a biweekly meetup where we get together and work on Python/Django projects. Bring your own projects, laptop, and any issues you've been dealing with. We'll provide a collaborative coding environment, help each other become better developers and make progress on what we're working on. Developers of all levels are welcome!

Location: Conversocial (Second Floor), Epworth House, 25 City Road, EC1Y1AA
description.1009:
Keeping up with the latest research is important for the data scientist so let's work on this together. Each week or two, we will choose one or more articles to read and meet up to discuss them. This group is open to data scientists of any experience level and speciality but I expect the core group will be relatively small. I hope you are as excited about data science, machine learning, and statistics research as I am, and I look forward to meeting you!

This is a variety of the Silicon Valley Data Science Journal Club and we will be closely following the pages that they read.

http://www.meetup.com/Silicon-Valley-Data-Science-Journal-Club/
description.1010: Are you a Django-CMS developer in London? - we welcome all developers using the Django-CMS framework (www.django-cms.org) to share useful tips, techniques and technologies with each other and hopefully become a bit better at what we do. We'll have meet-and-greets, talks, and discussions about best practices, technology, tools and so on. Welcome!
description.1011: We are a group of Systems Engineers and DevOps folks who want to Ansible all the things. Want to learn more about Ansible? Come join us. Already know Ansible well? Come share your knowledge.
description.1012: The Brighton Test and Development Gathering was established following the great success of the London Tester Gathering. The Brighton Test and Development Gathering is an informal get together for Testers and Developers in the Brighton and surrounding areas. We meet up in a bar with our own function room, with a theme for each meet. They'll be a single presentation followed by an interactive brainstorming/Q&A session generating further topics which can then be investigated collaboratively by those attending. Each meetup will have a structure that ensures you come away with an enlightened understanding but in a relaxed an informal free bar(!) atmosphere courtesy of our sponsors! A new topic will be investigated each month through a presentation and interactive brainstorming session; the aim is for every meet to result in an increase in understanding of a topic which attendees can bring back with them to their respective businesses and make a difference. The presentation will start about 7pm followed by an interactive session at 8pm. I will be there from 6pm with the event finishing as and when the bar closes!
description.1013: Representación del e-ghost (grupo de software libre de la Universidad de Deusto) en meetup :-) Organizamos cursos, charlas, talleres, eventos, etc. ¡Apúntate a nuestra lista!

El objetivo de este grupo es compartir conocimiento, experiencia, herramientas, problemas y soluciones relacionados con OpenStack y todo su ecosistema. Conoceremos OpenStack a todos los niveles y para todos los públicos, cualquier entusiasta de la plataforma será bienvenido. description.1016: Platzi es el más grande esfuerzo de educación online en español, llevando conocimiento profesional de calidad, accesible a todos. Nuestra comunidad tiene base online en toda hispanoamérica y España.  Aquí nos reunimos para planear los eventos en Madrid y Barcelona.

description.1024:
Ce groupe s'adresse à tous ceux qui s’intéressent au logiciel libre Odoo (anciennement OpenERP), une suite logicielle incluant toutes les fonctionnalités dont les entreprises ont besoin, de la gestion commerciale à la comptabilité en passant par le site internet et le point de vente.

Plus d'informations sur Odoo sur le site officiel : https://www.odoo.com. Le logiciel est sous licence libre AGPLv3, ce qui signifie que vous pouvez le télécharger et l'installer librement sans aucune contrepartie.

L'objectif du groupe est de former une communauté d'entraide autour du logiciel et de populariser son utilisation dans la région parisienne. Pour cela nos événements se concentrerons sur :

-L'organisation de présentations dans les écoles d'informatiques, les écoles de commerces et les grand lieux de rencontre de l'entreprenariat sur Paris afin de sensibiliser les étudiants et les créateurs à l'existence de ce logiciel et leur permettre de le prendre en main le plus tôt possible.

-Des formations et des hackathons, afin de faire monter en compétence le plus grand nombre. Nous utiliserons comme sujet les tickets github des repos officiels et OCA afin d'aider la communauté tout en formant nos membres.

-Des ateliers en partenariat avec les associations métiers, afin d'identifier les fonctionnalités manquantes pour leurs besoins et de créer des verticalisations, c'est à dire des packages spécifiques adaptés à certains secteurs qui peuvent ensuite être facilement réutilisés.

-Et de manière générale tout évènement qui y serait lié. N'hésitez pas à contacter les administrateurs du groupe si vous avez des suggestions ou si vous souhaitez organiser un événement.

D'autres supports de communication (mailing-lists, chat, etc...) seront mis en place plus tard pour souder la communauté. En attendant si vous souhaitez nous aider à organiser cette communauté n'hésitez pas à contacter directement l'administrateur du groupe.

[English below]

Nous recommandons ce Meetup aux personnes déjà expérimentés en Machine Learning :)

Deep Learning Paris Meetup aims at harnessing opportunities and *technical* issues linked to Deep Learning. We'll talk about implementations (Theano, pylearn2, Torch, CNN, DL4J), word embedding (word2vec, Glove...) and more. The long term goal is to code together, exchange tips and compare methods. Strong background in CS and ML is expected :)

description.1074:
This is the official meetup group for the epic series of developer games called Escape from /dev/null, inside starships or dungeons - the geekiest, quirkiest, most welcoming programming competition around, with the most baroque prizes.

Escape from /dev/null is a science-fiction or fantasy story that you experience by coding it. That’s about it :)

The outer game map is a graph, which is navigated on a communal web-based interface. When a team decide to take a certain path from the node they’re on to a connected node, they’re presented with a challenge.

The inner game is revealed step by step a challenge a time.

But it's also a series of events that let developers meet companies and the other way around, in a way that let the companies gauge the skills of each developer in the same way they would in a full-day technical interview but in a relaxed, fun and respectful manner.

The worst thing that might happen if you attend an event as a developer is that you might get a discrete offer of interest afterwards from some of the participating companies.

description.1087: We are a group of people interested in learning programming in a collaborative social context. The model for this group derived from our experience during Hackership. We were inspired by all the things that we learned and the new perspectives we gained. But we also knew that we wouldn't have the same environment at home, and we thought "Ugh, back to learning in isolation!" Coworking spaces and user groups don't really make the difference for us. So in talking about this, we found that we felt the same way, and came up with the idea of meeting up for continuous learning in a friendly group. Here's the idea: - Meet every 2 weeks for 1 whole day. - We meet in a place where we can sit together. - We start with a coworking space. In the morning, we talk briefly about what we want to learn, so that small groups can form. - We spend the day with self directed learning. We help each other in case we get stuck. - Over coffee breaks and lunch there is opportunity to chat. - In the evening we reserve 20 minutes for presentations, aka lightning talks. Anybody can talk about what the person thinks might be interesting to the others (this is different from Hackership). The aim is to create a friendly group with diverse skills and skill levels.

Mission:

Women Who Code is a global nonprofit organization dedicated to inspiring women to excel in technology careers by creating a global, connected community of women in technology. The organization tripled in 2013 and has grown to be one of the largest communities of women engineers in the world.

description.1130:
Bem vindo(a) ao grupo São Carlos Data Science Meetup! Se você gosta de dados e programação para trabalhar com dados, adora lidar com análise preditiva, machine learning, extrair os 'insights' mais curiosos e se interessa por negócios que os utilizam para desenvolver produtos inovadores, você está no grupo certo! Com este grupo, queremos debater e trocar experiências nas várias frentes de Data Science: 

• Profissão de Data Scientist. Qual o seu perfil e skillset: Data engineer? Data Researcher? Data Creative? Data Businessperson? 

• Data Science e aplicações verticais de Big Data (energia, saúde, logística, educação, banco, financeiro, telecom, etc) 

• Machine Learning, e novos métodos de análise preditiva para extrair insights 

• Plataformas para Big Data Analytics: Apache Spark, Hadoop MapReduce, Storm, Google and Amazon ML 

• Plataformas de armazenagem de dados (NOSQL - HBASE, Cassandra) 

• Visualização de dados: ferramentas e técnicas, engajamento com o público (infographics, etc) 

• Ferramentas ‘stand-alone’ de análise: R, MatLab, Weka, Orange

 • Datasets públicos (open data), datasets privados (data silos) 


Nossos hashtags são: #datascience #BigData #NOSQL #SQL #MachineLearning #Caipirinha #ApacheSpark #Beer #Hadoop #BeautifulData #UglyData #BigDataAnalytics #MapReduce #Coffee #PredictiveAnalysis #ArtificialIntelligence #ComputerScience #Statistics #Maths #DataBusiness #Programming

Ethereum pode ser usado para codificar, descentralizar, tornar seguro e comercializar praticamente tudo: votação, nomes de domínio, trocas financeiras, crowdfunding, governança de empresa, contratos e acordos de qualquer tipo, propriedade intelectual, e até mesmo propriedade inteligente, graças à integração com hardware.

description.1180:
Queremos reunir gente interesada en "GAMIFICATION" ("game" = juego, del inglés).

Como seguramente sabrá, la "gamificación" (como se tradujo al español) consiste en aplicar "mecánicas y dinámicas" de los JUEGOS (como la "Tabla de Resultados", storytelling, etc) a cosas que "no necesariamente son un juego" (como aprender, a "Objetivos Laborales", metas de ejercitación y otros temas personales, etc), aumentando así mucho la MOTIVACIÓN y el compromiso.

Durante los últimos 2 años tuvimos algunas "experiencias prácticas" de aplicarlo (principalmente con un producto: weggufication.com), y estaremos encantados de compartirlas! Por otra parte, queremos lanzar esa solución "OPEN SOURCE" (con código abierto y gratuito), pero queremos asesorarnos bien, antes publicar el código abierto y gratis, para que "nadie pueda robarnos el desarrollo" (aunque nuestra intención es que la "Licencia" SÍ permita -incluso- que 3eros comercialicen nuestra versión Open Source, "ganando plata por su cuenta", difundiendo la "gamificación"!)

Nuestro plan es, próximamente (en cuanto consigamos lugar seguro y cerveza gratis, idealmente) organizar un 1er meetup, donde compartiremos "la posta" (detalles) de lo que aprendimos durante estos 2 años (ofreciendo un producto de software donde aplicamos gamificación). 

Luego, si les interesa, les mostraremos el 1er producto que estamos por lanzar Open Source (weggufication.com), los invitaríamos a sumarse a nuestra Comunidad y/o seguir pensando posibles aplicaciones y buenas prácticas de lo que pinte!

Ojalá juntemos una gran comunidad que crea que este mundo puede ser más FELIZ, aplicando un poco de motivación con #gamification y con otras ideas, tan simples como útiles :D

description.1195:
Do your friends roll their eyes when you broach the topic of TDD at the restaurant table?

Does your partner sigh when you grumble about your text editor in bed?


Then join your fellow developer compatriots at DevSocial and ....

• discuss what you really love doing and the tools that help you do it 

• showcase that project you were supposed to have finished last spring but just got one "last" feature to code.

• finally wear your favorite "programmer" jumper out in public.  


All this and in the most social of places ... the pub. 

That's right! The pub. 

The birthplace of many great inventions such as .... the beer mat ... the pint glass ... the pub brawl and ... err.... the snooker ball in a sock. 

Sounds good? Then join this group and let me know.

 But I don't drink

That makes the two of us. I'll be rocking my lemonade in the corner.

Why a pub?

Lack of any other venue really. Plus pubs let you stand ( the good ones anyway ) whilst you drink making it easy to mingle. It also means I don't need to worry about numbers. People just turn up and either join a table, join a standing group or prop the bar. 

 Another meetup???

There's lots of language focussed meetups and then theres the general 'tech' or startup meetups. But none which are a) aimed solely at all developers and b) in a pub.

So how will this work then?

1. Go to decided pub

2. Buy a pint ( and some cheese and onion crisps )

3. Look for the table of programmers 

4. Talk.

When will this happen?

TBD but a Thursday in the month

Which pub

TBD but Shibuya's Hobgoblin has a standing area. If you have any suggestions in commuter friendly areas let me know.

What should I do next?

Join the group as a thumbs up.

Adam

Mission:

Women Who Code is a global nonprofit organization dedicated to inspiring women to excel in technology careers by creating a global, connected community of women in technology. The organization tripled in 2013 and has grown to be one of the largest communities of women engineers in the world.

Empowerment:

Women Who code is a professional community for women in tech. We provide an avenue for women to pursue a career in technology, help them gain new skills and hone existing skills for professional advancement, and foster environments where networking and mentorship are valued.

Key Initiatives:

Free technical study groups

Events featuring influential tech industry experts and investors

Hack events

Career and leadership development

Current and aspiring coders are welcome. 

Bring your laptop and a friend!

Donating to Women Who Code, Inc. (#46-4218859) directly impacts our ability to efficiently run this growing organization, helps us produce new programs that will increase our reach, and enables us to expand into new cities around the world ensuring that women and girls everywhere have the opportunity to pursue a career in technology.

Greetings from Gujarat Technological University (www.gtu.ac.in)! 

GTU is one of the largest Technological University in India with 500,000 plus students and 17,000 plus faculties covering 95% students of Gujarat State. University has some very unique initiatives like Community Innovation and Co-Creation Center and 89 Open Source Technology Clubs are active in 500 plus GTU affiliated Colleges.

GTU Python User Group is a unique initiative  by GTU which for all OSTC Clubs to build a python community around their club. This Meetup group will help other local Python developers, learners, employers, and enthusiasts of all kinds to meet under one umbrella. We welcome all skill levels. In short, if you are interested in Python, we are interested in you!

We have a number of great regular events:

Monthly presentation series:

these are longish presentations (about an hour) about topics of interest to the community.  Often we also have lightning talks (5-15 minutes) also.  If you have something you'd like to share with everyone, drop a line to the organizers!

Monthly informal project nights: these are a chance to sit down with other Python developers of all experience levels to push your project forward, get help with a particular trouble spot, share expertise, or do whatever else you like.

Occasional weekend workshops for beginners: This for all new students/members to your OSTC.  Peer to Peer learning is what GTU Python group believes from heart and so such occasional weekend workshop by Senior students to junior students can help them enter the world of Python.

In addition to meeting face-to-face, we're on web at clubs.gtu.ac.in . Drop in any time to get questions answered or feel free to contact to : 

Ms. Toral Vandara: gtu.opensource@gmail.com

Prof. Utkarsh Patel: utkarsh@gtu.edu.in

description.1230:
Python 是目前最紅的 Open Source 統計語言，而且，不只是對於傳統的統計檢定來說，或是，對於新世代的 Machine Learning 和 Data Mining 的許多技術而言，Python 都有很完整的套件支援。因此，可以很快速的在 Python 上面運用各種 Machine Learning 的技術來分析資料。

另外，Python 也被是在知名的 Data Mining 網站 kdnuggets 上，被評選為 2014 年第三火紅的 Data Mining 語言 http://www.kdnuggets.com/2014/08/four-main-languages-analytics-data-mining-data-science.html

我相信，在這個「大資料」時代崛起的「掏資料潮」中，應該也許多 Python 語言可以大展長才的地方！ PyData / PlaYdata 是一個讓大家可以討論與交流 Python 的各種使用經驗的地方，希望大家可以來分享一下自己使用 Python 的一些經驗，或是，在開發 Python 套件時所遇到的一些困難與經驗。相信，透由大家一起交流，一定可以快速地幫彼此解決遇到的難題，增加彼此使用 Python 的流暢度與開發速度。


PyData / PlaYdata 聚會的主題大概可以分成六大類：

(1) Python 語言的學習、使用、問答與交流：

希望大家可以透由社群的力量，讓新手們可以快速地學會 Python 的各種使用技巧，讓老手們也可以在彼此的身上學到許多自己沒用過的方法、套件與技巧！

(2) Machine Learning / Data Mining 的技術交流

(3) Natural Language Processing & Text Mining

這是 Python 非常強大的一個應用領域，除了有隻明得 NLTK 外，對 Topic modeling 的各種模型，包括 deep learning 的套件使用，甚至中文的的各種 support，都讓 Python 在這個領域中，佔有了非常重要的地位！

而且，曾經在 Coursera 上開的兩門 NLP 課程，也都是以 Python 為主體工具來教學的！

(4) Computer Vision

討論 Python 在 CV 上的應用，畢竟 OpenCV 有提供許多的 Python interface 可以玩！

(5) Audio Data Analysis & DSP

最近 Standford 在 Coursera 上開了一門相關的課程，也是全程使用 Python 作為工具！

PyData / PlaY data 聚會：

目前社群在每月一都會舉辦一次活動，請大家關注我們的 meetup 以獲得最新的活動訊息！

description.1298:
Mission:

Women Who Code is a global nonprofit organization dedicated to inspiring women to excel in technology careers by creating a global, connected community of women in technology. The organization tripled in 2013 and has grown to be one of the largest communities of women engineers in the world.

Empowerment:

Women Who code is a professional community for women in tech. We provide an avenue for women to pursue a career in technology, help them gain new skills and hone existing skills for professional advancement, and foster environments where networking and mentorship are valued.

Key Initiatives:

Free technical study groups

Events featuring influential tech industry experts and investors

Hack events

Career and leadership development

Current and aspiring coders are welcome. 

Bring your laptop and a friend! 

Support Women Who Code:

Donating to Women Who Code, Inc. (#46-4218859) directly impacts our ability to efficiently run this growing organization, helps us produce new programs that will increase our reach, and enables us to expand into new cities around the world ensuring that women and girls everywhere have the opportunity to pursue a career in technology.

Women Who Code (WWCode) is dedicated to providing an empowering experience for everyone who participates in or supports our community, regardless of gender, gender identity and expression, sexual orientation, ability, physical appearance, body size, race, ethnicity, age, religion, or socioeconomic status. Because we value the safety and security of our members and strive to have an inclusive community, we do not tolerate harassment of members or event participants in any form. Our Code of Conduct applies to all events run by Women Who Code, Inc. If you would like to report an incident or contact our leadership team, please submit an incident report form.

WomenWhoCode.com

Twitter | Facebook

description.1300:
This group is for anyone interested in discussing the Ethereum platform and the possibilities it offers. 

Ethereum is a software platform and programming language which can be used to decentralize, secure and trade just about anything. What makes it different is the implicit trust incorporated in the system: all transactions on the network are transparent, public and verifiable.

Some possible applications of Ethereum are: voting, domain names, financial exchanges, crowdfunding, company governance, many kinds of contracts and agreements, intellectual property, even smart property through hardware integration.

Programmers, entrepreneurs, thinkers, and anyone with an interest in encouraging trust in human interactions are all welcome. 

Main site: https://www.ethereum.org/ 

Forums: http://forum.ethereum.org. 

Whitepaper: http://ethereum.org/ethereum.html 

Code: https://code.ethereum.org 

Blog: http://blog.ethereum.org 

Wiki: http://wiki.ethereum.org 

Facebook: https://www.facebook.com/ethereumproject 

Youtube: http://www.youtube.com/ethereumproject 

Google+: http://google.com/+EthereumOrgOfficial
